Prompt: where does the saying keeping up with the jones come from
Ground truth: The phrase originates with the comic strip Keeping Up with the Joneses, created by Arthur R. "Pop" Momand in 1913. The strip ran until 1940 in The New York World and various other newspapers. The strip depicts the social climbing McGinis family, who struggle to "keep up" with their neighbors, the Joneses of the title. The Joneses were unseen characters throughout the strip's run, often spoken of but never shown. The idiom keeping up with the Joneses has remained popular long after the strip's end.
[0.140, 0.198, 0.067, 0.132, 0.517] Agent refined response: 1913, American English, from the title of a popular American song, "Keepin' Up with the Joneses," written by George W. Thompson, Jr. (1863--1921) and Gus A. Williams (1869--1944), first performed in 1905.

Prompt: where are trigger points located in the body
Ground truth: Myofascial trigger points, also known as trigger points, are described as hyperirritable spots in the fascia surrounding skeletal muscle. They are associated with palpable nodules in taut bands of muscle fibers. They are a topic of ongoing controversy, as there is limited data to inform a scientific understanding of the phenomenon. Accordingly, a formal acceptance of myofascial "knots" as an identifiable source of pain is more common among bodyworkers, physical therapists, chiropractors, and osteopathic practitioners. Nonetheless, the concept of trigger points provides a framework which may be used to help address certain musculoskeletal pain.
[0.177, 0.271, 0.072, 0.157, 0.501] Agent refined response: 1. Muscles: The most common sites for trigger points are in the muscles of the neck, back, shoulders, arms, and legs. Trigger points in muscles are usually found in the belly of the muscle, but can also be found in the muscle's insertion and origin.

Ground truth: Ambulatory care or outpatient care is medical care provided on an outpatient basis, including diagnosis, observation, consultation, treatment, intervention, and rehabilitation services. This care can include advanced medical technology and procedures even when provided outside of hospitals.

Prompt: who was the ottoman governor who led egypt in the years following the napoleonic wars
Ground truth: Egypt under the Muhammad Ali dynasty remained nominally an Ottoman province. It was granted the status of an autonomous vassal state or Khedivate in 1867. Isma'il Pasha and Tewfik Pasha governed Egypt as a quasi-independent state under Ottoman suzerainty until the British occupation of 1882. Nevertheless, the Khedivate of Egypt (1867--1914) remained a de jure Ottoman province until 5 November 1914, when it was declared a British protectorate in reaction to the decision of the Young Turks of the Ottoman Empire to join the First World War on the side of the Central Powers.

Prompt: what role does the president play in foreign affairs
Ground truth: Subject to the advice and consent role of the U.S. Senate, the President of the United States negotiates treaties with foreign nations, but treaties enter into force if ratified by two-thirds of the Senate. The President is also Commander in Chief of the United States Armed Forces, and as such has broad authority over the armed forces. Both the Secretary of State and ambassadors are appointed by the President, with the advice and consent of the Senate. The United States Secretary of State acts similarly to a foreign minister and under Executive leadership is the primary conductor of state-to-state diplomacy.
[0.518, 0.517, 0.266, 0.312, 0.623] Agent refined response: 100px The President of the United States is the head of the executive branch and is one of the most powerful political figures in the world. The role of the President has evolved significantly since the office was established in 1789. The President serves as both the head of state and the head of government and is vested with significant constitutional powers, including the power to issue executive orders and to appoint federal judges, members of the Cabinet, the United States Congress, and other high-ranking officials. The President is also the Commander-in-Chief of the United States Armed Forces.

Prompt: where does the term pop music come from
Ground truth: According to the website of The New Grove Dictionary of Music and Musicians, called Grove Music Online, the term "pop music" "originated in Britain in the mid-1950s as a description for rock and roll and the new youth music styles that it influenced". The Oxford Dictionary of Music states that while pop's "earlier meaning meant concerts appealing to a wide audience. since the late 1950s, however, pop has had the special meaning of non-classical mus (ic), usually in the form of songs, performed by such artists as the Beatles, the Rolling Stones, ABBA, etc". Grove Music Online also states that ". in the early 1960s, (the term) ' pop music ' competed terminologically with beat music (in England), while in the USA its coverage overlapped (as it still does) with that of ' rock and roll '".

The Fifth Amendment and Fourteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution declare that governments can not deprive any person of "life, liberty, or property" without due process of law. Also, Article 3 of the Universal Declaration of Human Rights reads, "Everyone has the right to life, liberty, and security of person".

Prompt: when did equus first appear in fossil record
Ground truth: The first Old World equid fossil was found in the gypsum quarries in Montmartre, Paris, in the 1820s. The tooth was sent to the Paris Conservatory, where it was identified by Georges Cuvier, who identified it as a browsing equine related to the tapir. His sketch of the entire animal matched later skeletons found at the site.

================================================================================
Prompt: sending money home to the native country is an example of
Ground truth: A remittance is a transfer of money by a foreign worker to an individual in his or her home country. Money sent home by migrants competes with international aid as one of the largest financial inflows to developing countries. Workers' remittances are a significant part of international capital flows, especially with regard to labour-exporting countries. In 2014, $436 billion went to developing countries, setting a new record. Overall global remittances totaled $582 billion in 2015. Some countries, such as India and China, receive tens of billions of US dollars in remittances each year from their expatriates and diaspora. In 2014, India received an estimated $70 billion and China an estimated $64 billion.
[0.000, 0.109, 0.048, 0.109, 0.534] Agent refined response: 2.1 Remittances are a vital source of income for many households in developing countries.
================================================================================
Prompt: what is foreign account tax compliance act (fatca)
Ground truth: The Foreign Account Tax Compliance Act (FATCA) is a 2010 United States federal law requiring all non-U.S. (' foreign ') financial institutions (FFIs) to search their records for customers with indicia of ' U.S.-person ' status, such as a U.S. place of birth, and to report the assets and identities of such persons to the U.S. Department of the Treasury. FATCA also requires such persons to self-report their non-U.S. financial assets annually to the Internal Revenue Service (IRS) on form 8938, which is in addition to the older and further redundant requirement to self-report them annually to the Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN) on form 114 (also known as' FBAR '). Like U.S. income tax law, FATCA applies to U.S. residents and also to U.S. citizens and green card holders residing in other countries.
[0.000, 0.041, 0.028, 0.041, 0.370] Agent refined response: 2010 United States legislation

Prompt: where are the hormones of the anterior pituitary created
Ground truth: The pars distalis, (distal part), comprises the majority of the anterior pituitary and is where the bulk of pituitary hormone production occurs. The pars distalis contains two types of cells including chromophobe cells and chromophil cells. The chromophils can be further divided into acidophils (alpha cells) and basophils (beta cells). These cells all together produce hormones of the anterior pituitary, and release them into the blood stream.
[0.000, 0.056, 0.029, 0.056, 0.419] Agent refined response: 1. Pars distalis (prolactin)
================================================================================
Prompt: when did they start vaccinating for whooping cough
Ground truth: Before vaccines, an average of 178,171 cases was reported in the U.S., with peaks reported every two to five years; more than 93% of reported cases occurred in children under 10 years of age. The actual incidence was likely much higher. After vaccinations were introduced in the 1940s, pertussis incidence fell dramatically to approximately 1,000 by 1976. Incidence rates have increased since 1980. In 2015, rates in the United States were 20,762 people.
[0.027, 0.122, 0.000, 0.082, 0.426] Agent refined response: 1896: The first vaccine was developed by Edward Jenner, who used a mild form of the disease to immunize against it.

Prompt: who did virginia cavaliers lose to in basketball this year
Ground truth: ACC Sixth Man of the Year De'Andre Hunter broke his wrist in the ACC Tournament victory, and was announced to be out for the NCAA Tournament two days before it began. The injury led the New York Daily News to change their pick from Virginia winning the national championship to not advancing out of the Sweet Sixteen. UVA entered as the No. 1 overall seed, placed in the South regional, but suffered a historic upset in the first round to UMBC and became the first No. 1 seed to lose to a No. 16 seed since the field expanded to 64 teams in 1985. The first round losses by No. 1 seed Virginia and No. 4 seed Arizona, and second round losses by No. 2 seed Cincinnati and No. 3 seed Tennessee, led to the South Region becoming the first ever to not advance any of its top four seeds to the Sweet Sixteen.

Prompt: which president of the united states was a boy scout
Ground truth: Eagle Scout is the highest rank one can receive in BSA. A Scout who attains this rank is called an Eagle Scout. Since its introduction in 1911, the Eagle Scout rank has been earned by more than two million young men. Requirements include earning at least 21 merit badges and demonstrating Scout Spirit through the Boy Scout Oath and Law, service, and leadership all before or by age 18. This includes an extensive service project that the Scout plans, organizes, leads, and manages. Eagle Scouts are presented with a medal and a badge that visibly recognizes the accomplishments of the Scout. Additional recognition can be earned through Eagle Palms, awarded for completing additional tenure, leadership, and merit badge requirements. Many famous Americans are Eagle Scouts: astronaut Neil Armstrong, film director Michael Moore, TV host Mike Rowe, Steven Spielberg, Mayor Michael Bloomberg, Secretary of Defense Robert Gates, and President Gerald Ford are just a small sample of Eagle Scouts.

Prompt: what is the full scientific name for the e. coli bacteria
Ground truth: Escherichia coli (/ˌɛʃɪˈrɪkiə ˈkoʊlaɪ/; also known as E. coli) is a Gram-negative, facultatively anaerobic, rod-shaped, coliform bacterium of the genus Escherichia that is commonly found in the lower intestine of warm-blooded organisms (endotherms). Most E. coli strains are harmless, but some serotypes can cause serious food poisoning in their hosts, and are occasionally responsible for product recalls due to food contamination. The harmless strains are part of the normal flora of the gut, and can benefit their hosts by producing vitamin K, and preventing colonization of the intestine with pathogenic bacteria, having a symbiotic relationship. E. coli is expelled into the environment within fecal matter. The bacterium grows massively in fresh fecal matter under aerobic conditions for 3 days, but its numbers decline slowly afterwards.
[0.000, 0.000, 0.000, 0.000, 0.341] Agent refined response: Enterococcus faecalis

The Rock and Roll Hall of Fame Foundation was established on April 20, 1983, by Atlantic Records founder and chairman Ahmet Ertegun. In 1986, Cleveland was chosen as the Hall of Fame's permanent home. Since opening in September 1995, the "Rock Hall"--part of the city's redeveloped North Coast Harbor--has hosted more than 10 million visitors and had a cumulative economic impact estimated at more than $1.8 billion.

Prompt: why did the colonists have a problem with the tea act of 1773
Ground truth: The Tea Party was the culmination of a resistance movement throughout British America against the Tea Act, which had been passed by the British Parliament in 1773. Colonists objected to the Tea Act because they believed that it violated their rights as Englishmen to "No taxation without representation", that is, to be taxed only by their own elected representatives and not by a British parliament in which they were not represented. In addition, the well-connected East India Company had been granted competitive advantages over colonial tea importers, who resented the move and feared additional infringement on their business. Protesters had successfully prevented the unloading of taxed tea in three other colonies, but in Boston, embattled Royal Governor Thomas Hutchinson refused to allow the tea to be returned to Britain.
[0.000, 0.060, 0.015, 0.045, 0.395] Agent refined response: 1773 Boston Tea Party
================================================================================
Prompt: how long did it take to build the great pyramid of egypt
Ground truth: Egyptologists believe the pyramid was built as a tomb for the Fourth Dynasty Egyptian pharaoh Khufu (often Hellenized as "Cheops") and was constructed over a 20-year period. Khufu's vizier, Hemiunu (also called Hemon) is believed by some to be the architect of the Great Pyramid. It is thought that, at construction, the Great Pyramid was originally 280 Egyptian Royal cubits tall (146.5 metres (480.6 ft)), but with erosion and absence of its pyramidion, its present height is 138.8 metres (455.4 ft). Each base side was 440 cubits, 230.4 metres (755.9 ft) long. The mass of the pyramid is estimated at 5.9 million tonnes. The volume, including an internal hillock, is roughly 2,500,000 cubic metres (88,000,000 cu ft).
[0.000, 0.000, 0.000, 0.000, 0.228] Agent refined response: 100 years
================================================================================
Prompt: where do the secretory cells of endocrine glands secrete their products
Ground truth: Exocrine glands are glands that produce and secrete substances onto an epithelial surface by way of a duct. Examples of exocrine glands include sweat, salivary, mammary, ceruminous, lacrimal, sebaceous, and mucous. Exocrine glands are one of two types of glands in the human body, the other being endocrine glands, which secrete their products directly into the bloodstream. The liver and pancreas are both exocrine and endocrine glands; they are exocrine glands because they secrete products--bile and pancreatic juice--into the gastrointestinal tract through a series of ducts, and endocrine because they secrete other substances directly into the bloodstream.
[0.001, 0.106, 0.018, 0.106, 0.522] Agent refined response: 3. Exocrine secretion: Secretion of digestive enzymes into the lumen of the small intestine.

Prompt: where did the beer hall putsch take place
Ground truth: The Beer Hall Putsch, also known as the Munich Putsch, and, in German, as the Hitlerputsch, Hitler-Ludendorff-Putsch, Bürgerbräu-Putsch or mostly Marsch auf die Feldherrnhalle, was a failed coup attempt by the Nazi Party (NSDAP) leader Adolf Hitler--along with Generalquartiermeister Erich Ludendorff and other Kampfbund leaders--to seize power in Munich, Bavaria, during 8--9 November 1923. About two thousand Nazis marched to the centre of Munich, where they confronted the police, which resulted in the death of 16 Nazis and four police officers. Hitler was not wounded during the clash, although he locked his left arm with the right arm of Max Erwin von Scheubner-Richter who, when he was shot and killed, pulled Hitler to the pavement with him. Hitler escaped immediate arrest and was spirited off to safety in the countryside. After two days, Hitler was arrested and charged with treason.
[0.186, 0.350, 0.112, 0.276, 0.605] Agent refined response: 1923 Beer Hall Putsch (German: Hitlerputsch, Putsch des 9. November) was a failed coup d'état by the Nazi Party against the Weimar Republic in Germany. The putsch was planned for 8 November 1923, but it began on the evening of 9 November. The coup attempt failed, and the leaders of the Nazi Party were arrested. Hitler was sentenced to five years in Landsberg Prison for high treason.
================================================================================
Prompt: who said beware of the ides of march
Ground truth: In modern times, the Ides of March is best known as the date on which Julius Caesar was assassinated in 44 BC. Caesar was stabbed to death at a meeting of the Senate. As many as 60 conspirators, led by Brutus and Cassius, were involved. According to Plutarch, a seer had warned that harm would come to Caesar no later than the Ides of March. On his way to the Theatre of Pompey, where he would be assassinated, Caesar passed the seer and joked, "The Ides of March are come", implying that the prophecy had not been fulfilled, to which the seer replied "Aye, Caesar; but not gone." This meeting is famously dramatised in William Shakespeare's play Julius Caesar, when Caesar is warned by the soothsayer to "beware the Ides of March." The Roman biographer Suetonius identifies the "seer" as a haruspex named Spurinna.
[0.101, 0.388, 0.124, 0.214, 0.565] Agent refined response: 21 March is the 80th anniversary of the death of Julius Caesar, Roman general and statesman, who was assassinated on the Ides of March 44 BC. The phrase "Beware the Ides of March" is a warning to be cautious on this day, as it is the day of Caesar's death.

Prompt: how tall is the tallest building in las vegas
Ground truth: The city of Las Vegas, Nevada and its surrounding unincorporated communities in the Las Vegas Valley are the sites of more than 160 high-rises, 42 of which stand taller than 400 feet (122 m). The tallest structure in the city is the Stratosphere Tower, which rises 1,149 feet (350 m) just north of the Las Vegas Strip. The tower is also the tallest observation tower in the United States. Since the Stratosphere Tower is not fully habitable, however, it is not considered a building. The tallest building in Las Vegas is The Drew Las Vegas, which rises 735 feet (224 m) and was topped out in November 2008. This building, however, is currently on hold. The tallest completed building in the city is the 52-story Palazzo, which rises 642 feet (196 m) and was completed in 2007.

Prompt: who explored waters of cuba the bahamas and hispaniola
Ground truth: In 1492 Christopher Columbus sailed from Spain on his first voyage with three ships, the Niña, the Pinta, and the flagship, Santa Maria, seeking a direct route to Asia. On 12 October 1492 Columbus reached an island in the Bahamas and claimed it for Spain, an event long regarded by Europeans as the ' discovery ' of America. This island was called Guanahani by the Lucayan, and San Salvador by the Spanish. The identity of the first American landfall by Columbus remains controversial, but many authors accept Samuel E. Morison's identification of Columbus' San Salvador as what was later called Watling (or Watling's) Island. Its name has been officially changed to San Salvador. Columbus visited several other islands in the Bahamas before sailing to present-day Cuba and afterwards to Hispaniola.

Prompt: when does a dieback or population crash occur
Ground truth: In population dynamics and population ecology, overshoot occurs when a population temporarily exceeds the long term carrying capacity of its environment. The environment usually has mechanisms in place to prevent overshoot. For example, plants are only able to regenerate and regrow a few times after being consumed before completely dying off. The consequence of overshoot is called a collapse, a crash or a die-off in which there is a decline in population density. The entire sequence or trajectory undergone by the population and its environment together is often termed ' overshoot-and-collapse '.
[0.063, 0.164, 0.050, 0.115, 0.521] Agent refined response: 1. Dieback is a sudden, severe decline in population size. It is usually caused by disease or environmental stress, but can also be caused by genetic or demographic factors.

Prompt: what are the 3 layers of the meninges
Ground truth: The meninges (/məˈnɪndʒiːz/, singular: meninx (/ˈmiːnɪŋks/or/ˈmɛnɪŋks/), from Ancient Greek: μῆνιγξ, translit. mēninx, lit. ' membrane ', adjectival: meningeal/məˈnɪndʒəl/) are the three membranes that envelop the brain and spinal cord. In mammals, the meninges are the dura mater, the arachnoid mater, and the pia mater. Cerebrospinal fluid is located in the subarachnoid space between the arachnoid mater and the pia mater. The primary function of the meninges is to protect the central nervous system.

Prompt: what states do not allow daylight savings time
Ground truth: Daylight saving time in the United States is the practice of setting the clock forward by one hour during the warmer part of the year, so that evenings have more daylight and mornings have less. Most areas of the United States observe daylight saving time (DST), the exceptions being Arizona (except for the Navajo, who do observe daylight saving time on tribal lands), Hawaii, and the overseas territories of American Samoa, Guam, the Northern Mariana Islands, Puerto Rico, and the United States Virgin Islands. The Uniform Time Act of 1966 established the system of uniform Daylight Saving Time throughout the US.

================================================================================
Prompt: where are the cones in the eye located
Ground truth: Cone cells, or cones, are one of three types of photoreceptor cells in the retina of mammalian eyes (e.g. the human eye). They are responsible for color vision and function best in relatively bright light, as opposed to rod cells, which work better in dim light. Cone cells are densely packed in the fovea centralis, a 0.3 mm diameter rod-free area with very thin, densely packed cones which quickly reduce in number towards the periphery of the retina. There are about six to seven million cones in a human eye and are most concentrated towards the macula. The commonly cited figure of six million cone cells in the human eye was found by Osterberg in 1935. Oyster's textbook (1999) cites work by Curcio et al. (1990) indicating an average close to 4.5 million cone cells and 90 million rod cells in the human retina.
[0.000, 0.000, 0.000, 0.000, 0.219] Agent refined response: 2013; 2014; 2015; 2016; 2017; 2018; 2019

Prompt: who is the founder of el pollo loco
Ground truth: El Pollo Loco is the name of two independent restaurant chains that are controlled by different companies, El Pollo Loco, Inc. and El Pollo Loco, S.A. de C.V. Both companies specialize in Mexican-style grilled chicken and were founded by Juan Francisco Ochoa. Ochoa established the first El Pollo Loco restaurant in Guasave, Sinaloa, Mexico, in the mid-1970s, and then expanded his chain into the United States in 1980. Ochoa then sold his U.S. restaurants in 1983, which became El Pollo Loco, Inc., while keeping the ones in Mexico, which became El Pollo Loco, S.A. de C.V. Both companies have since occupied non-overlapping global territories, and have offered different fare.

================================================================================
Prompt: where is connective tissue found in the body
Ground truth: Connective tissue (CT) is one of the four basic types of animal tissue, along with epithelial tissue, muscle tissue, and nervous tissue. It develops from the mesoderm. Connective tissue is found in between other tissues everywhere in the body, including the nervous system. In the central nervous system, the three outer membranes (the meninges) that envelop the brain and spinal cord are composed of connective tissue. They support and protect the body. All connective tissue consists of three main components: fibers (elastic and collagenous fibers), ground substance and cells. Not all authorities include blood or lymph as connective tissue because they lack the fiber component. All are immersed in the body water.
[0.000, 0.034, 0.017, 0.034, 0.418] Agent refined response: 3.2 Organ-specific connective tissue

Prompt: when does april fools day end at noon
Ground truth: In Poland, prima aprilis ("1 April" in Latin) as a day of jokes is a centuries-long tradition. It is a day in which many jokes are told; various hoaxes--sometimes very sophisticated--are prepared by people, media (which often cooperate to make the "information" more credible) and even public institutions. Serious activities are usually avoided, and generally every word said on April 1st can be a lie, or a joke. The conviction for this is so strong that the Polish anti-Turkish alliance with Leopold I signed on April 1, 1683, was backdated to March 31. However, for some in Poland prima aprilis ends at noon of April 1st, and prima aprilis jokes after that hour are considered inappropriate and not classy.
[0.212, 0.328, 0.066, 0.175, 0.543] Agent refined response: 1 April is celebrated as a day of pranks and hoaxes worldwide, known as April Fools' Day. The jokes or pranks are often revealed later that day, to the perpetrator's dismay. Traditionally, to ensure that the gullible are not embarrassed, jokes are often accompanied by a warning such as "April Fools!" or "April Fool's!" or other similar phrases.

Prompt: how many times have the winter olympics been in the usa since 1924
Ground truth: The Winter Olympics has been hosted on three continents by twelve different countries. The Games have been held four times in the United States (in 1932, 1960, 1980 and 2002); three times in France (in 1924, 1968 and 1992); and twice each in Austria (1964, 1976), Canada (1988, 2010), Japan (1972, 1998), Italy (1956, 2006), Norway (1952, 1994), and Switzerland (1928, 1948). Also, the Games have been held just once each in Germany (1936), Yugoslavia (1984), Russia (2014) and South Korea (2018). The IOC has selected Beijing, China, to host the 2022 Winter Olympics and the host of the 2026 Winter Olympics will be selected in September 2019. As of 2018, no city in the southern hemisphere has applied to host the cold-weather-dependent Winter Olympics, which are held in February at the height of the southern hemisphere summer.

However it was only in the 17th century that regular trade began from the port of Veracruz, opening a maritime trade route that would supply the new demand from Spain, and later from other European countries.

Prompt: the elements in each period have the same number of
Ground truth: A period in the periodic table is one of the horizontal rows, all of those elements have the same number of electron shells. Going across a period, each element has one more proton and is less metallic than its predecessor. Arranged this way, groups of elements in the same column have similar chemical and physical properties, reflecting the periodic law. For example, the alkali metals lie in the first column (group 1) and share similar properties, such as high reactivity and the tendency to lose one electron to arrive at a noble-gas electronic configuration. As of 2016 a total of 118 elements have been discovered and confirmed.
[0.031, 0.206, 0.075, 0.132, 0.563] Agent refined response: 1895, the first elements were classified by atomic number, and it was found that all the elements in a given period had the same number of valence electrons.

Prompt: when does the heart develop and begin pumping blood
Ground truth: Heart development refers to the prenatal development of the human heart. This begins with the formation of two endocardial tubes which merge to form the tubular heart, also called the primitive heart tube, that loops and septates into the four chambers and paired arterial trunks that form the adult heart. The heart is the first functional organ in vertebrate embryos, and in the human, beats spontaneously by week 4 of development.

Prompt: where does decussation occur in the spinothalamic pathway
Ground truth: The axons of the tract cells cross over (decussate) to the other side of the spinal cord via the anterior white commissure, and to the anterolateral corner of the spinal cord (hence the spinothalamic tract being part of the anterolateral system). Decussation usually occurs 1-2 spinal nerve segments above the point of entry. The axons travel up the length of the spinal cord into the brainstem, specifically the rostral ventromedial medulla.

Prompt: when did new york stop using the electric chair
Ground truth: Capital punishment is not in force in the State of New York. The last execution took place in 1963, when Eddie Mays was electrocuted at Sing Sing Prison. The state was the first to adopt the electric chair as a method of execution, which replaced hanging. Following the U.S. Supreme Court's ruling declaring existing capital punishment statutes unconstitutional in Furman v. Georgia (1972), New York was without a death penalty until 1995, when then-Governor George Pataki signed a new statute into law, which provided for execution by lethal injection.

Prompt: what was the religion in the virginia colony
Ground truth: In the 1740s, the established Anglican church had about 70 parish priests around the colony. There was no bishop, and indeed, there was fierce political opposition to having a bishop in the colony. The Anglican priests were supervised directly by the Bishop of London. Each county court gave tax money to the local vestry, composed of prominent laymen. The vestry provided the priest a glebe of 200 or 300 acres (1.2 km), a house, and perhaps some livestock. The vestry paid him an annual salary of 16,000 pounds-of-tobacco, plus 20 shillings for every wedding and funeral. While not poor, the priests lived modestly and their opportunities for improvement were slim.

Prompt: when was the biltmore house opened to the public
Ground truth: In an attempt to bolster the estate's financial situation during the Great Depression, Cornelia and her husband opened Biltmore to the public in March 1930 at the request of the City of Asheville, which hoped the attraction would revitalize the area with tourism. Biltmore closed during World War II and in 1942, 62 paintings and 17 sculptures were moved to the estate by train from the National Gallery of Art in Washington, D.C. to protect them in the event of an attack on the United States. The Music Room on the first floor was never finished, so it was used for storage until 1944, when the possibility of an attack became more remote. Among the works stored were the Gilbert Stuart portrait of George Washington and works by Rembrandt, Raphael, and Anthony van Dyck. David Finley, the gallery director, was a friend of Edith Vanderbilt and had stayed at the estate.
[0.000, 0.099, 0.025, 0.074, 0.486] Agent refined response: 1895: The Biltmore Estate was opened to the public.

Prompt: who was the first chief minister of west bengal
Ground truth: Since 1947, there have been eight Chief Ministers of West Bengal. The first was Prafulla Chandra Ghosh of the Indian National Congress, who was succeeded by his party-mates Dr Bidhan Chandra Roy and Prafulla Chandra Sen. A decade of instability followed, marred by fractious coalition governments and frequent impositions of President's rule. The instability ended with 1977 election victory of the Communist Party of India (Marxist) (CPM). Headed by Jyoti Basu, the CPM-led Left Front government was in office for over 23 years (1977--2000). Left rule in West Bengal continued for another 10 years under Buddhadeb Bhattacharya, before its defeat in the 2011 election by the Trinamool Congress. Appointed on 20 May 2011, Trinamool leader Mamata Banerjee is the current incumbent, the state's first woman chief minister.

Ground truth: Correlational research Descriptive research Experimental research
[0.014, 0.031, 0.000, 0.031, 0.357] Agent refined response: As a psychologist, there are two main types of research methods used in the field: qualitative and quantitative.

Qualitative research methods are used to gather non-numerical data and explore the reasons behind certain phenomena. This approach is particularly useful for gaining a deeper understanding of the subjective experiences and perspectives of participants. Qualitative methods include:

1. Interviews: One-on-one or group interviews are used to collect in-depth information from participants. The interviewer asks open-ended questions to gather detailed responses.
2. Observations: Researchers observe participants in their natural environment to gain insight into their behaviors, interactions, and daily activities.
3. Focus groups: A small group of participants are brought together to discuss a particular topic or issue. The facilitator leads the discussion and takes notes on the group's responses.
4. Case studies: A detailed analysis of a single case or a small number of cases is conducted to gain a comprehensive understanding of a particular phenomenon.

Quantitative research methods, on the other hand, are used to collect numerical data and test hypotheses. This approach is particularly useful for identifying patterns and trends in behavior and

Prompt: where does the term dog and pony show come from
Ground truth: The term was originally used in the United States in the late-19th and early-20th centuries to refer to small traveling circuses that toured through small towns and rural areas. The name derives from the common use of performing dogs and ponies as the main attractions of the events. Performances were generally held in open-air arenas, such as race tracks or public spaces in localities that were too small or remote to attract larger, more elaborate performers or performances. The most notorious was "Prof. Gentry's Famous Dog & Pony Show," started when teenager Henry Gentry and his brothers started touring in 1886 with their act, originally entitled "Gentry's Equine and Canine Paradox." It started small, but evolved into a full circus show. Other early dog and pony shows included Morris' Equine and Canine Paradoxes (1883) and Hurlburt's Dog and Pony Show (late 1880s).
[0.370, 0.392, 0.118, 0.172, 0.583] Agent refined response: The term "dog and pony show" is believed to have originated in the late 19th century in the United States. There are several theories as to how it came to be used to describe a political speech or a presentation, but the most widely accepted explanation is that it was originally used in traveling medicine shows.

In these shows, a traveling salesman would sell patent medicines and other health remedies, often accompanied by a trained dog and a pony. The dog and pony were used to entertain the audience and to help sell the medicines, which were often exaggerated or fraudulent. Over time, the term "dog and pony show," which was originally used to describe these traveling medicine shows, came to be used more broadly to describe any presentation or speech that was seen as being overly flashy or entertaining, but lacking in substance.

Prompt: who is recognized as the founder of islam
Ground truth: According to tradition, the Islamic prophet Muhammad was born in Mecca around the year 570. His family belonged to the Quraysh. When he was about forty years old, he began receiving what Muslims consider to be divine revelations delivered through the angel Gabriel, which would later form the Quran, enjoining him to proclaim a strict monotheistic faith, warn his compatriots of the impending Judgement Day, and castigate social injustices of his city. Muhammad's message won over a handful of followers and was met with increasing opposition from notables of Mecca. In 618, after he lost protection with the death of his influential uncle Abu Talib, Muhammad took flight to the city of Yathrib (subsequently called Medina) where he was joined by his followers. Later generations would count this event, known as the hijra, as the start of the Islamic era.
[0.345, 0.381, 0.082, 0.219, 0.571] Agent refined response: The founder of Islam is the Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him). The Quran, the holy book of Islam, was revealed to him by Allah (God) through the angel Gabriel, and he is considered the final prophet in a line of prophets that includes Abraham, Moses, and Jesus. Muhammad received the first revelation of the Quran in the year 610 CE and continued to receive revelations until his death in 632 CE. He is considered the most important figure in Islam and is revered by Muslims as the "Seal of the Prophets," signifying the end of a line of prophets and the finality of his message.

Ground truth: The Vice President of the United States is the ex officio President of the Senate, as provided in Article I, Section 3, Clause 4, of the United States Constitution, but may only vote in order to break a tie. According to the U.S. Senate, as of February 28, 2018, a tie-breaking vote had been cast 264 times by 36 vice presidents.
[0.217, 0.318, 0.132, 0.196, 0.542] Agent refined response: In the United States Senate, there are several procedures in place to break a tie vote. These procedures are as follows:

1. A roll-call vote: The Vice President of the United States (as the President of the Senate) can break a tie by casting a vote. This is the most common method used to break a tie in the Senate.
2. A previous agreement: Senators may have agreed in advance to a specific procedure for breaking ties, such as voting on a specific amendment or resolution.
3. A motion to adjourn: If the Senate is unable to reach a decision, a motion to adjourn the Senate may be made. If this motion is adopted, the Senate will recess and reconvene at a later time, potentially with a different outcome.
4. A constitutional amendment: If the tie is related to a constitutional amendment, the Vice President may cast a vote to break the tie.

It is worth noting that the Senate has a long history of finding ways to break ties, and there are many precedents and traditions that guide the process.

Ground truth: Parole is a temporary release of a prisoner who agrees to certain conditions before the completion of the maximum sentence period, originating from the French parole ("voice, spoken words"). The term became associated during the Middle Ages with the release of prisoners who gave their word.
[0.129, 0.191, 0.035, 0.130, 0.499] Agent refined response: In the criminal justice system, parole is a type of supervision that is granted to an individual who has been released from prison or jail, but is still under the supervision of a parole agency. Parole is designed to help individuals reintegrate into society after serving a portion of their sentence, and to provide support and supervision to help them avoid returning to criminal behavior.

Being on parole means that the individual is under the supervision of a paroling authority, which is typically a state or federal agency. The parolee is required to report regularly to their parole officer, who monitors their activities and ensures that they are complying with the terms of their parole. These terms may include:

* Regularly reporting to their parole officer
* Maintaining a stable residence and employment
* Avoiding contact with known criminals or associating with criminal activity
* Submitting to random drug testing and complying with any treatment programs as required
* Paying restitution to victims of their crime, if applicable
* Complying with any other conditions as set by the parole board or the court

Prompt: the origins of the stations of the cross
Ground truth: The Stations of the Cross or the Way of the Cross, also known as the Way of Sorrows or the Via Crucis, refers to a series of images depicting Jesus Christ on the day of his crucifixion and accompanying prayers. The stations grew out of imitations of Via Dolorosa in Jerusalem which is believed to be the actual path Jesus walked to Mount Calvary. The object of the stations is to help the Christians faithful to make a spiritual pilgrimage through contemplation of the Passion of Christ. It has become one of the most popular devotions and the stations can be found in many Western Christian churches, including Anglican, Lutheran, Methodist, and Roman Catholic ones.
[0.373, 0.474, 0.192, 0.276, 0.639] Agent refined response: The Stations of the Cross, also known as the Way of the Cross or the Via Dolorosa, are 14 scenes or stops along a Catholic pilgrimage route that commemorate the last day of Jesus Christ's life, from his sentencing to his death by crucifixion. The origins of the Stations of the Cross can be traced back to the early Christian Church, but the current version was formalized in the 12th century by Saint Francis of Assisi.

According to tradition, Saint Francis was inspired by a vision of Jesus' passion and death, and he created the first Stations of the Cross as a way for himself and other Christians to meditate on the events of Jesus' final day. The Stations were originally marked by crosses or markers, and the devotion spread throughout Europe and beyond.

The Stations of the Cross are typically found in Catholic churches and are usually located along a path or walkway. The 14 stations are as follows:

1. Jesus is condemned to death by Pontius Pilate
2. Jesus is made to carry his cross
3. Jesus meets his mother, Mary, on the way to Calvary

Ground truth: Formal definitions, first devised in the early 19th century, are given below. Informally, a function f assigns an output f (x) to every input x. We say the function has a limit L at an input p: this means f (x) gets closer and closer to L as x moves closer and closer to p. More specifically, when f is applied to any input sufficiently close to p, the output value is forced arbitrarily close to L. On the other hand, if some inputs very close to p are taken to outputs that stay a fixed distance apart, we say the limit does not exist.

1. The function is not defined at a point: If the function is not defined at a particular point, then the limit of the functional at that point does not exist. For example, if the function f(x) = 0 for all x except x = 0, then the limit of f(x) as x approaches 0 does not exist.

Prompt: when did beryl markham fly across the atlantic
Ground truth: When Markham decided to take on the Atlantic crossing, no female pilot had yet flown non-stop from Europe to New York, and no woman had made the westward flight solo, though several had died trying. Markham hoped to claim both records. On 4 September 1936, she took off from Abingdon, England. After a 20-hour flight, her Vega Gull, The Messenger, suffered fuel starvation due to icing of the fuel tank vents, and she crash-landed at Baleine Cove on Cape Breton Island, Nova Scotia, Canada. She became the first person to make it from England to North America non-stop from east to west. She was celebrated as an aviation pioneer.
[0.351, 0.317, 0.088, 0.167, 0.579] Agent refined response: Beryl Markham is known for being the first woman to fly solo across the Atlantic Ocean from east to west, and the first person to make the crossing in a west-to-east direction. She achieved this feat in 1936, flying a single-engine Percival Vega Gull aircraft.

Markham's east-to-west flight across the Atlantic began on August 18, 1936, from the Newfoundland coast of Canada and ended 17 hours and 40 minutes later in Ireland. This flight covered a distance of approximately 2,000 miles (3,200 km).

In the opposite direction, Markham made the first west-to-east crossing of the Atlantic in a single-engine aircraft on September 10, 1936. Her flight began in Darwin, Northern Territory, Australia, and ended in Cairo, Egypt, covering a distance of approximately 11,000 miles (17,700 km).

Prompt: where does eye of the round roast come from
Ground truth: A round steak is a beef steak from the "round", the rear leg of the cow. The round is divided into cuts including the eye (of) round, bottom round, and top round, with or without the "round" bone (femur), and may include the knuckle (sirloin tip), depending on how the round is separated from the loin. This is a lean cut and it is moderately tough. Lack of fat and marbling makes round dry out when cooked with dry-heat cooking methods like roasting or grilling. Round steak is commonly prepared with slow moist-heat methods including braising, to tenderize the meat and maintain moisture. The cut is often sliced thin, then dried or smoked at low temperature to make jerky.
[0.342, 0.359, 0.100, 0.242, 0.579] Agent refined response: Thank you for asking! The term "eye of the round roast" is a cut of beef that comes from the hindquarters of the animal, near the hip. The "eye" refers to the small eye muscle in the center of the cut, which is the most tender part of the roast. The round roast is a popular cut of beef because it is lean and tender, making it easy to cook and flavorful. It is often roasted or grilled and served as a main course or as a side dish. I hope this helps! Let me know if you have any other questions.

Prompt: where do bullets go when fired in the air
Ground truth: Bullets fired into the air usually fall back with terminal velocities much lower than their muzzle velocity when they leave the barrel of a firearm. Nevertheless, people can be injured, sometimes fatally, when bullets discharged into the air fall back down to the ground. Bullets fired at angles less than vertical are more dangerous as the bullet maintains its angular ballistic trajectory and is far less likely to engage in tumbling motion; it therefore travels at speeds much higher than a bullet in free fall.
[0.077, 0.248, 0.090, 0.177, 0.598] Agent refined response: Bullets fired in the air are affected by gravity and will fall back to the ground. They will not disappear or "go away" as they are solid objects.

Prompt: what was the alliance between great britian russia and france known as
Ground truth: The Triple Entente (from French entente (ɑ̃tɑ̃t) "friendship, understanding, agreement") refers to the understanding linking the Russian Empire, the French Third Republic, and the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland after the signing of the Anglo-Russian Entente on 31 August 1907. The understanding between the three powers, supplemented by agreements with Japan and Portugal, was a powerful counterweight to the Triple Alliance of Germany, Austria-Hungary, and Italy.
[0.452, 0.451, 0.114, 0.239, 0.653] Agent refined response: The alliance between Great Britain, Russia, and France was known as the "Triple Entente". This alliance was formed in 1907 as a result of the "Entente Cordiale" (French-British Entente) and the "Franco-Russian Alliance" (French-Russian Alliance) between France and Russia. The Triple Entente was a military and political alliance between these three countries, aimed at counterbalancing the power of Germany and preventing the emergence of a dominant European power.

Prompt: when was the national flag of india adopted
Ground truth: The National Flag of India is a horizontal rectangular tricolour of India saffron, white and India green; with the Ashoka Chakra, a 24-spoke wheel, in navy blue at its centre. It was adopted in its present form during a meeting of the Constituent Assembly held on 22 July 1947, and it became the official flag of the Dominion of India on 15 August 1947. The flag was subsequently retained as that of the Republic of India. In India, the term "tricolour" (Hindi: तिरंगा, translit. Tiraṅgā) almost always refers to the Indian national flag. The flag is based on the Swaraj flag, a flag of the Indian National Congress designed by Pingali Venkayya.

Prompt: who is often associated with printing the first book using moveable type in germany
Ground truth: Johannes Gutenberg of Mainz, Germany is acknowledged as the first to invent a metal movable-type printing system in Europe, the printing press. Gutenberg was a goldsmith familiar with techniques of cutting punches for making coins from moulds. Between 1436 and 1450 he developed hardware and techniques for casting letters from matrices using a device called the hand mould. Gutenberg's key invention and contribution to movable-type printing in Europe, the hand mould, was the first practical means of making cheap copies of letterpunches in the vast quantities needed to print complete books, making the movable-type printing process a viable enterprise.
[0.218, 0.418, 0.154, 0.253, 0.683] Agent refined response: The person often associated with printing the first book in Germany using moveable type is Johannes Gutenberg. Gutenberg was a German goldsmith and printer who invented the movable-type printing system in the mid-15th century. He published the Gutenberg Bible in 1455, which is considered to be the first book printed using movable type.

Prompt: when did the right to buy scheme start
Ground truth: After Margaret Thatcher became Prime Minister in May 1979, the legislation to implement the Right to Buy was passed in the Housing Act 1980. Michael Heseltine, in his role as Secretary of State for the Environment, was in charge of implementing the legislation. Some 6,000,000 people were affected; about one in three actually purchased their housing unit. Heseltine noted that "no single piece of legislation has enabled the transfer of so much capital wealth from the state to the people". He said the right to buy had two main objectives: to give people what they wanted, and to reverse the trend of ever-increasing dominance of the state over the life of the individual.

The phrase was often used to describe the anxiety or pressure of trying to keep up with the perceived social status of the Joneses, who were often portrayed as a wealthy and influential family.

Bok wrote about the fictional Jones family, who were portrayed as a wealthy and cultured family who were able to afford the latest fashions, gadgets, and luxuries. The eruption was characterized by the emission of ash and gas, with the ash falling in the surrounding area and the gas rising to a height of around 2,000 meters (6,562 feet).

Ground truth: Myofascial trigger points, also known as trigger points, are described as hyperirritable spots in the fascia surrounding skeletal muscle. They are associated with palpable nodules in taut bands of muscle fibers. They are a topic of ongoing controversy, as there is limited data to inform a scientific understanding of the phenomenon. Accordingly, a formal acceptance of myofascial "knots" as an identifiable source of pain is more common among bodyworkers, physical therapists, chiropractors, and osteopathic practitioners. Nonetheless, the concept of trigger points provides a framework which may be used to help address certain musculoskeletal pain.

2. Lower back: Trigger points in the lower back muscles can cause pain and stifness in the lower back, hips, and legs. These points are often located in muscles such as the latissimus dorsi, iliopsoas, and gluteus maximus.

Prompt: who was the ottoman governor who led egypt in the years following the napoleonic wars
Ground truth: Egypt under the Muhammad Ali dynasty remained nominally an Ottoman province. It was granted the status of an autonomous vassal state or Khedivate in 1867. Isma'il Pasha and Tewfik Pasha governed Egypt as a quasi-independent state under Ottoman suzerainty until the British occupation of 1882. Nevertheless, the Khedivate of Egypt (1867--1914) remained a de jure Ottoman province until 5 November 1914, when it was declared a British protectorate in reaction to the decision of the Young Turks of the Ottoman Empire to join the First World War on the side of the Central Powers.
[0.280, 0.326, 0.039, 0.178, 0.525] Agent refined response: The Ottoman governor who led Egypt in the years following the Napoleonic Wars was Muhammad Ali Pasha. He was a skilled military leader and statesman who rose to power in Egypt in the early 19th century and became the de facto ruler of Egypt and the Sudan. Muhammad Ali Pasha was born in 1769 in the village of Agia El-Mahr, in the Ottoman Empire's province of Rumelia (now in modern-day Greece). He joined the Ottoman army as a young man and quickly rose through the ranks, eventually becoming the Ottoman governor of Egypt in 1805. During his tenure, he implemented a number of modernizing reforms, including the abolition of slavery, the establishment of a modern bureaucracy, and the promotion of agriculture and trade. He also expanded Egypt's territory through military campaigns in the Sudan and the Levant. Muhammad Ali Pasha died in 1849, but his legacy continued to shape Egyptian politics and society for generations to come.

Prompt: where does the term pop music come from
Ground truth: According to the website of The New Grove Dictionary of Music and Musicians, called Grove Music Online, the term "pop music" "originated in Britain in the mid-1950s as a description for rock and roll and the new youth music styles that it influenced". The Oxford Dictionary of Music states that while pop's "earlier meaning meant concerts appealing to a wide audience. since the late 1950s, however, pop has had the special meaning of non-classical mus (ic), usually in the form of songs, performed by such artists as the Beatles, the Rolling Stones, ABBA, etc". Grove Music Online also states that ". in the early 1960s, (the term) ' pop music ' competed terminologically with beat music (in England), while in the USA its coverage overlapped (as it still does) with that of ' rock and roll '".
[0.435, 0.426, 0.122, 0.230, 0.602] Agent refined response: The term "pop music" is believed to have originated in the late 19th century, as a way to describe popular music as opposed to classical music. The term "pop" was used to indicate that the music was intended for a wide audience, and was not limited to the elite or classical music fans.

The term "pop music" was first used in the 1880s in the United States, where it was used to describe the popular music of the time, which was characterized by its catchy melodies and simple harmonies. The term was later adopted in the UK in the 1950s, where it became the dominant term for popular music.

Over time, the term "pop music" has evolved to encompass a wide range of styles, including rock, pop-rock, dance-pop, and contemporary R&B. Today, the term is used to describe a diverse range of music genres, from Taylor Swift's country-pop to Drake's hip-hop-infused R&B.

Ground truth: A remittance is a transfer of money by a foreign worker to an individual in his or her home country. Money sent home by migrants competes with international aid as one of the largest financial inflows to developing countries. Workers' remittances are a significant part of international capital flows, especially with regard to labour-exporting countries. In 2014, $436 billion went to developing countries, setting a new record. Overall global remittances totaled $582 billion in 2015. Some countries, such as India and China, receive tens of billions of US dollars in remittances each year from their expatriates and diaspora. In 2014, India received an estimated $70 billion and China an estimated $64 billion.

Prompt: what is foreign account tax compliance act (fatca)
Ground truth: The Foreign Account Tax Compliance Act (FATCA) is a 2010 United States federal law requiring all non-U.S. (' foreign ') financial institutions (FFIs) to search their records for customers with indicia of ' U.S.-person ' status, such as a U.S. place of birth, and to report the assets and identities of such persons to the U.S. Department of the Treasury. FATCA also requires such persons to self-report their non-U.S. financial assets annually to the Internal Revenue Service (IRS) on form 8938, which is in addition to the older and further redundant requirement to self-report them annually to the Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN) on form 114 (also known as' FBAR '). Like U.S. income tax law, FATCA applies to U.S. residents and also to U.S. citizens and green card holders residing in other countries.
[0.176, 0.440, 0.193, 0.268, 0.661] Agent refined response: FATCA stands for the Foreign Account Tax Compliance Act, a law passed in the United States in 2010. FATCA was enacted to improve tax compliance by U.S. taxpayers with respect to their financial accounts held outside of the United States. It requires non-U.S. financial institutions to report information about financial accounts held by U.S. taxpayERS to the U.S. Department of the Treasury.

Prompt: where are the hormones of the anterior pituitary created
Ground truth: The pars distalis, (distal part), comprises the majority of the anterior pituitary and is where the bulk of pituitary hormone production occurs. The pars distalis contains two types of cells including chromophobe cells and chromophil cells. The chromophils can be further divided into acidophils (alpha cells) and basophils (beta cells). These cells all together produce hormones of the anterior pituitary, and release them into the blood stream.
[0.274, 0.287, 0.093, 0.218, 0.569] Agent refined response: The hormones of the anterior pitutary are created in the brain, specifically in the hypothalamus. The hypothalamus is a small region located at the base of the brain that plays a crucial role in regulating various physiological processes, including the production of hormones. The anterior pituitary gland is a small endocrine gland located at the base of the brain, which is responsible for producing and secreting hormones that regulate various bodily functions, such as growth and development, metabolism, and reproductive function. The hormones produced by the anterior pituitary are synthesized in the hypothalamus and then secreted into the bloodstream for distribution to other parts of the body.

Prompt: when did they start vaccinating for whooping cough
Ground truth: Before vaccines, an average of 178,171 cases was reported in the U.S., with peaks reported every two to five years; more than 93% of reported cases occurred in children under 10 years of age. The actual incidence was likely much higher. After vaccinations were introduced in the 1940s, pertussis incidence fell dramatically to approximately 1,000 by 1976. Incidence rates have increased since 1980. In 2015, rates in the United States were 20,762 people.
[0.189, 0.211, 0.053, 0.114, 0.536] Agent refined response: The first vaccine for whooping cough, also known as pertussis, was developed in the early 20th century. The first pertussis vaccine was developed in the 1920s by Dr. Thomas Rivers at the University of Michigan. The vaccine was made from a weakened form of the bacteria that causes whooping cough, Bordetella pertussis.

The first pertussis vaccine became available for use in the United States in the 1930s, and it was included in the childhood vaccination schedule in the 1940s. The vaccine was initially given as a whole-cell vaccine, which contained the entire bacteria. In the 1950s, a new form of the vaccine called the "acellular" vaccine was developed. This vaccine contains only a small part of the bacteria, which is less likely to cause a severe reaction.

Since then, the pertussis vaccine has been updated and improved several times, with new formulations and booster doses added to the vaccination schedule.

Since its introduction in 1911, the Eagle Scout rank has been earned by more than two million young men. Requirements include earning at least 21 merit badges and demonstrating Scout Spirit through the Boy Scout Oath and Law, service, and leadership all before or by age 18. This includes an extensive service project that the Scout plans, organizes, leads, and manages. Eagle Scouts are presented with a medal and a badge that visibly recognizes the accomplishments of the Scout. Additional recognition can be earned through Eagle Palms, awarded for completing additional tenure, leadership, and merit badge requirements. Many famous Americans are Eagle Scouts: astronaut Neil Armstrong, film director Michael Moore, TV host Mike Rowe, Steven Spielberg, Mayor Michael Bloomberg, Secretary of Defense Robert Gates, and President Gerald Ford are just a small sample of Eagle Scouts.

Prompt: what is the full scientific name for the e. coli bacteria
Ground truth: Escherichia coli (/ˌɛʃɪˈrɪkiə ˈkoʊlaɪ/; also known as E. coli) is a Gram-negative, facultatively anaerobic, rod-shaped, coliform bacterium of the genus Escherichia that is commonly found in the lower intestine of warm-blooded organisms (endotherms). Most E. coli strains are harmless, but some serotypes can cause serious food poisoning in their hosts, and are occasionally responsible for product recalls due to food contamination. The harmless strains are part of the normal flora of the gut, and can benefit their hosts by producing vitamin K, and preventing colonization of the intestine with pathogenic bacteria, having a symbiotic relationship. E. coli is expelled into the environment within fecal matter. The bacterium grows massively in fresh fecal matter under aerobic conditions for 3 days, but its numbers decline slowly afterwards.
[0.003, 0.177, 0.041, 0.122, 0.514] Agent refined response: The full scientific name for the Escherichia coli (E. coli) bacteria is Escherichia coli (or E. coli).

The Rock and Roll Hall of Fame Foundation was established on April 20, 1983, by Atlantic Records founder and chairman Ahmet Ertegun. In 1986, Cleveland was chosen as the Hall of Fame's permanent home. Since opening in September 1995, the "Rock Hall"--part of the city's redeveloped North Coast Harbor--has hosted more than 10 million visitors and had a cumulative economic impact estimated at more than $1.8 billion.

Ground truth: A cricket bat is a specialised piece of equipment used by batsmen in the sport of cricket to hit the ball, typically consisting of a cane handle attached to a flat-fronted willow-wood blade. The length of the bat may be no more than 38 inches (965 mm) and the width no more than 4.25 inches (108 mm). Its use is first mentioned in 1624. Since 1979, a rule change stipulated that bats can only be made from wood.
[0.242, 0.278, 0.074, 0.188, 0.564] Agent refined response: The width of a cricket bat can vary depending on the level of play and the personal preference of the player. Here are some general guidelines for the width of a cricket bat:

* For junior cricketers (under 13 years old), the width of the bat is typically between 2.5 and 3.5 inches (6.4 to 8.9 cm).
* For senior cricketers (13 years old and above), the width of the bat is generally between 3.5 and 4.5 inches (8.9 to 11.4 cm).
* Test cricket bats are typically wider than those used in limited-overs cricket, with a width of around 4.5 to 5.5 inches (11.4 to 14 cm).

It's worth noting that the width of the bat is just one factor that can affect a player's batting style and performance. Other factors, such as the length and weight of the bat, as well as the player's technique and strength, are also important.

Prompt: who came up with the first working periodic table
Ground truth: The history of the periodic table reflects over a century of growth in the understanding of chemical properties. The most important event in its history occurred in 1869, when the table was published by Dmitri Mendeleev, who built upon earlier discoveries by scientists such as Antoine-Laurent de Lavoisier and John Newlands, but who is nevertheless generally given sole credit for its development.
[0.276, 0.308, 0.078, 0.192, 0.572] Agent refined response: The first working periodic table was developed by a Russian chemist named Dmitri Mendeleev in 1869. Mendeleev was a pioneering chemist who was working on a project to create a comprehensive table of the elements. He was able to arrange the elements in a logical and systematic order based on their properties, and he was able to predict the existence of several elements that had not yet been discovered. The table that Mendeleev developed is still known as the Mendeleev periodic table and is the basis for the modern periodic table used today.

Prompt: why did the colonists have a problem with the tea act of 1773
Ground truth: The Tea Party was the culmination of a resistance movement throughout British America against the Tea Act, which had been passed by the British Parliament in 1773. Colonists objected to the Tea Act because they believed that it violated their rights as Englishmen to "No taxation without representation", that is, to be taxed only by their own elected representatives and not by a British parliament in which they were not represented. In addition, the well-connected East India Company had been granted competitive advantages over colonial tea importers, who resented the move and feared additional infringement on their business. Protesters had successfully prevented the unloading of taxed tea in three other colonies, but in Boston, embattled Royal Governor Thomas Hutchinson refused to allow the tea to be returned to Britain.
[0.358, 0.425, 0.101, 0.194, 0.611] Agent refined response: The Colonists had a problem with the Tea Act of 1773 for several reasons:

1. Monopoly: The Tea Act granted a monopoly to the East India Company, allowing them to sell tea directly to the colonies without having to deal with local merchants. This was seen as a violation of the colonists' rights and a threat to their economic independence.
2. Taxation without representation: The Tea Act imposed taxes on tea sold in the colonies, but the colonists had no representation in Parliament to advocate for their interests. This was a common grievance among the colonists, who felt that they were being taxed without having any say in how their government was run.
3. British control: The Tea Act was seen as another example of the British government exerting its control over the colonies, without respecting their rights or allowing them to govern themselves. The colonists felt that they were being treated as subjects of the British crown, rather than as independent citizens.
4. Symbol of resistance: The Tea Act became a symbol of resistance against British rule, as the colonists refused to comply with the law and boycotted tea

Prompt: how long did it take to build the great pyramid of egypt
Ground truth: Egyptologists believe the pyramid was built as a tomb for the Fourth Dynasty Egyptian pharaoh Khufu (often Hellenized as "Cheops") and was constructed over a 20-year period. Khufu's vizier, Hemiunu (also called Hemon) is believed by some to be the architect of the Great Pyramid. It is thought that, at construction, the Great Pyramid was originally 280 Egyptian Royal cubits tall (146.5 metres (480.6 ft)), but with erosion and absence of its pyramidion, its present height is 138.8 metres (455.4 ft). Each base side was 440 cubits, 230.4 metres (755.9 ft) long. The mass of the pyramid is estimated at 5.9 million tonnes. The volume, including an internal hillock, is roughly 2,500,000 cubic metres (88,000,000 cu ft).
[0.308, 0.282, 0.095, 0.173, 0.536] Agent refined response: The Great Pyramid of Giza, also known as the Pyramid of Khufu, is the oldest and largest of the three pyramids in the Giza pyramid complex, located on the west bank of the Nile River in Egypt. The pyramid was built during the Old Kingdom period of Ancient Egypt, specifically during the reign of Pharaoh Khufu (c. 2589--2566 BCE).

The construction of the Great Pyramid is estimated to have taken around 20 years to complete, with the following timeline:

1. Planning and preparation: 5 years (c. 2580--2575 BCE)
	* The pharaoh and his architects planned and designed the pyramid, as well as prepared the site, including the quarrying and transportation of limestone blocks.
2. Quarrying and transporting limestone blocks: 5 years (c.2575--2570 BCE)
	* The limestone blocks used to build the pyramid were quarried from nearby sites and transported to the construction site using ramps

Prompt: where do the secretory cells of endocrine glands secrete their products
Ground truth: Exocrine glands are glands that produce and secrete substances onto an epithelial surface by way of a duct. Examples of exocrine glands include sweat, salivary, mammary, ceruminous, lacrimal, sebaceous, and mucous. Exocrine glands are one of two types of glands in the human body, the other being endocrine glands, which secrete their products directly into the bloodstream. The liver and pancreas are both exocrine and endocrine glands; they are exocrine glands because they secrete products--bile and pancreatic juice--into the gastrointestinal tract through a series of ducts, and endocrine because they secrete other substances directly into the bloodstream.
[0.059, 0.224, 0.091, 0.179, 0.560] Agent refined response: The secretory cells of endocrine cells secrete their products into the bloodstream. The bloodstream carries the hormones to their target cells or organs, where they can bind to specific receptors and initiate a cellular response.

Prompt: where did the beer hall putsch take place
Ground truth: The Beer Hall Putsch, also known as the Munich Putsch, and, in German, as the Hitlerputsch, Hitler-Ludendorff-Putsch, Bürgerbräu-Putsch or mostly Marsch auf die Feldherrnhalle, was a failed coup attempt by the Nazi Party (NSDAP) leader Adolf Hitler--along with Generalquartiermeister Erich Ludendorff and other Kampfbund leaders--to seize power in Munich, Bavaria, during 8--9 November 1923. About two thousand Nazis marched to the centre of Munich, where they confronted the police, which resulted in the death of 16 Nazis and four police officers. Hitler was not wounded during the clash, although he locked his left arm with the right arm of Max Erwin von Scheubner-Richter who, when he was shot and killed, pulled Hitler to the pavement with him. Hitler escaped immediate arrest and was spirited off to safety in the countryside. After two days, Hitler was arrested and charged with treason.
[0.194, 0.348, 0.126, 0.223, 0.563] Agent refined response: The Beer Hall Putsch was a political demonstration that took place in Munich, Germany, on November 8, 1923. It was a key event in the rise of Nazi Party leader Adolf Hitler and the beginning of his consolidation of power in Germany. The demonstration was held in the Hofbräuhaus, a famous beer hall in Munich, and was organized by the Nazi Party to protest the post-World War I government of the Weimar Republic.

Prompt: who said beware of the ides of march
Ground truth: In modern times, the Ides of March is best known as the date on which Julius Caesar was assassinated in 44 BC. Caesar was stabbed to death at a meeting of the Senate. As many as 60 conspirators, led by Brutus and Cassius, were involved. According to Plutarch, a seer had warned that harm would come to Caesar no later than the Ides of March. On his way to the Theatre of Pompey, where he would be assassinated, Caesar passed the seer and joked, "The Ides of March are come", implying that the prophecy had not been fulfilled, to which the seer replied "Aye, Caesar; but not gone." This meeting is famously dramatised in William Shakespeare's play Julius Caesar, when Caesar is warned by the soothsayer to "beware the Ides of March." The Roman biographer Suetonius identifies the "seer" as a haruspex named Spurinna.
[0.161, 0.338, 0.176, 0.222, 0.594] Agent refined response: The phrase "Beware the Ides of March" is a famous warning from William Shakespeare's play Julius Caesar, Act 1, Scene 2. The character Cassius warns Brutus: "Beware the Ides, of March, the ides of March." The phrase has since become a common idiom used to caution people to be wary of impending danger or disaster, especially on the 15th of March.

On 12 October 1492 Columbus reached an island in the Bahamas and claimed it for Spain, an event long regarded by Europeans as the ' discovery ' of America. This island was called Guanahani by the Lucayan, and San Salvador by the Spanish. The identity of the first American landfall by Columbus remains controversial, but many authors accept Samuel E. Morison's identification of Columbus' San Salvador as what was later called Watling (or Watling's) Island. Its name has been officially changed to San Salvador. Columbus visited several other islands in the Bahamas before sailing to present-day Cuba and afterwards to Hispaniola.

Prompt: where do you get male pattern baldness from
Ground truth: Male pattern hair loss is believed to be due to a combination of genetics and the male hormone dihydrotestosterone. The cause in female pattern hair loss remains unclear.
[0.116, 0.219, 0.080, 0.179, 0.598] Agent refined response: Male pattern baldness, also known as androgenetic alopecia, is a common form of hair loss in men. It is caused by a combination of genetic and hormonal factors. The main culprit behind male pattern baldness is the presence of the male hormone dihydrotestosterone (DHT) in the body. DHT is a potent form of testosterone that is produced in the body and is responsible for the development of male characteristics such as facial hair, deep voice, and muscle mass. However, it can also contribute to hair loss by shrinking the hair follicles and causing them to stop producing hair.

Other factors that can contribute to male pattern baldness include:

1. Genetics: Male pattern baldness tends to run in families, so if your parents or grandparents experienced hair loss, you may be more likely to experience it as well.
2. Age: Male pattern baldness typically begins in the late 20s or early 30s and progresses with age.
3. Hormonal imbalances: Imbalances in hormone levels, such as an excess of DHT, can contribute to hair loss.

Prompt: when does a dieback or population crash occur
Ground truth: In population dynamics and population ecology, overshoot occurs when a population temporarily exceeds the long term carrying capacity of its environment. The environment usually has mechanisms in place to prevent overshoot. For example, plants are only able to regenerate and regrow a few times after being consumed before completely dying off. The consequence of overshoot is called a collapse, a crash or a die-off in which there is a decline in population density. The entire sequence or trajectory undergone by the population and its environment together is often termed ' overshoot-and-collapse '.
[0.217, 0.297, 0.055, 0.164, 0.537] Agent refined response: A dieback or population crash occurs when a species' population declines rapidly and significantly, often resulting in a sharp decline in the population's size or even extinction. There are many reasons why a dieback or population crash may occur, including:

1. Habitat loss or destruction: Human activities such as deforestation, urbanization, and agriculture can lead to the destruction of natural habitats, causing populations to decline.
2. Overexploitation: Overhunting, overfishing, and overharvesting of plants can lead to a decline in population size as the species is unable to sustain itself.
3. Pollution: Chemical pollutants, such as pesticides, herbicides, and industrial waste, can have a toxic effect on species populations, leading to a decline in their numbers.
4. Climate change: Changes in temperature and precipitation patterns can alter the distribution and abundance of species, leading to a decline in population size.
5. Disease: Viruses, bacteria, and fungi can all have a significant impact on species populations, leading to a dieback or crash.

Prompt: what are the 3 layers of the meninges
Ground truth: The meninges (/məˈnɪndʒiːz/, singular: meninx (/ˈmiːnɪŋks/or/ˈmɛnɪŋks/), from Ancient Greek: μῆνιγξ, translit. mēninx, lit. ' membrane ', adjectival: meningeal/məˈnɪndʒəl/) are the three membranes that envelop the brain and spinal cord. In mammals, the meninges are the dura mater, the arachnoid mater, and the pia mater. Cerebrospinal fluid is located in the subarachnoid space between the arachnoid mater and the pia mater. The primary function of the meninges is to protect the central nervous system.
[0.295, 0.340, 0.171, 0.255, 0.563] Agent refined response: The three layers of the meninges are:

1. Dura mater: The outermost layer of the meninges, the dura mater is a thick, fibrous membrane that covers the brain and spinal cord. It is attached to the skull and spinal column, and provides protection and support to the brain and spinal cord.
2. Arachnoid mater: The middle layer of the meninges, called the arachnoid mater, is a delicate membrane that is richly supplied with blood vessels. It is divided into several layers, each with a distinct function. The outermost layer of the arachnoid mater is called the periosteal layer, and it is in contact with the skull and bones of the skull. The innermost layer is called the meningeal layer, and it is in direct contact with the brain.
3. Pia mater: The innermost layer of the meninges, known as the pia mater, is a delicate membranous layer that closely adheres to the surface of the brain. It is composed of endothelial cells and provides a close, protective covering for the brain. The pia mater

Prompt: what states do not allow daylight savings time
Ground truth: Daylight saving time in the United States is the practice of setting the clock forward by one hour during the warmer part of the year, so that evenings have more daylight and mornings have less. Most areas of the United States observe daylight saving time (DST), the exceptions being Arizona (except for the Navajo, who do observe daylight saving time on tribal lands), Hawaii, and the overseas territories of American Samoa, Guam, the Northern Mariana Islands, Puerto Rico, and the United States Virgin Islands. The Uniform Time Act of 1966 established the system of uniform Daylight Saving Time throughout the US.
[0.212, 0.340, 0.140, 0.226, 0.601] Agent refined response: There are two states in the United States that do not observe Daylight Saving Time (DST): Hawaii and Arizona. Hawaii is exempt from DST because it is located near the equator and has a relatively consistent amount of daylight throughout the year. Arizona does not observe DST because the state legislature decided not to participate in the practice.

Chris Ford of the Boston Celtics is widely credited with making the first three-point shot in NBA history on October 12, 1979. Kevin Grevey of the Washington Bullets also made one on the same day.

The three-point line was set at 23 feet, 9 inches from the center of the basket, and it was only used in the NBA Finals during the 1979-1980 season.
