Prompt: where are the cones in the eye located
Ground truth: Cone cells, or cones, are one of three types of photoreceptor cells in the retina of mammalian eyes (e.g. the human eye). They are responsible for color vision and function best in relatively bright light, as opposed to rod cells, which work better in dim light. Cone cells are densely packed in the fovea centralis, a 0.3 mm diameter rod-free area with very thin, densely packed cones which quickly reduce in number towards the periphery of the retina. There are about six to seven million cones in a human eye and are most concentrated towards the macula. The commonly cited figure of six million cone cells in the human eye was found by Osterberg in 1935. Oyster's textbook (1999) cites work by Curcio et al. (1990) indicating an average close to 4.5 million cone cells and 90 million rod cells in the human retina.
[0.271, 0.365, 0.134, 0.216, 0.578] Agent refined response: The cones in the eye are located in the retina, which is the innermost layer of the eye. The retina is the light-sensitive tissue at the back of the eye that converts light into electrical signals that are transmitted to the brain. The cones are responsible for color vision and are found in the central part of the retina, known as the macula. The macula is a small, specialized area of the retina that is responsible for central vision and is responsible for activities such as reading, driving, and recognizing faces.

Both companies specialize in Mexican-style grilled chicken and were founded by Juan Francisco Ochoa. Ochoa established the first El Pollo Loco restaurant in Guasave, Sinaloa, Mexico, in the mid-1970s, and then expanded his chain into the United States in 1980. Ochoa then sold his U.S. restaurants in 1983, which became El Pollo Loco, Inc., while keeping the ones in Mexico, which became El Pollo Loco, S.A. de C.V. Both companies have since occupied non-overlapping global territories, and have offered different fare.

Lavine, a former business student and avid golfer, started the chain as a small take-out restaurant in a strip mall in Los Angeles. He named the restaurant "El Pollo Loco" (which means "the crazy chicken" in Spanish) because he had the idea of cooking chicken in a pressure fryer to create a crispy, juicy chicken breast. The restaurant quickly gained popularity for its flame-grilled chicken and became a successful chain with over 400 locations in the United States and internationally.

Prompt: where is connective tissue found in the body
Ground truth: Connective tissue (CT) is one of the four basic types of animal tissue, along with epithelial tissue, muscle tissue, and nervous tissue. It develops from the mesoderm. Connective tissue is found in between other tissues everywhere in the body, including the nervous system. In the central nervous system, the three outer membranes (the meninges) that envelop the brain and spinal cord are composed of connective tissue. They support and protect the body. All connective tissue consists of three main components: fibers (elastic and collagenous fibers), ground substance and cells. Not all authorities include blood or lymph as connective tissue because they lack the fiber component. All are immersed in the body water.
[0.280, 0.331, 0.099, 0.225, 0.584] Agent refined response: Connective tissue is found throughout the body and makes up a significant portion of the human body. It is found in the following areas:

1. Bones: Connective tissue is found in the bones, particularly in the bone marrow, where it helps to produce blood cells.
2. Muscles: Connective tissue is found between muscle fibers, where it helps to provide support and stability to the muscles.
3. Joints: Connective tissue is found around the joints, where it helps to cushion and support the joints and provide stability to the surrounding muscles and bones.
4. Blood vessels: Connective tissue is found surrounding blood vessels, where it helps to protect and support the vessels.
5. Nerves: Connective tissue is found near nerves, where it helps to protect and insulate the nerves.
6. Skin: Connective tissue is found beneath the skin, where it helps to provide support, stability, and protection to the skin.
7. Eyes: Connective tissue is found within the eyes, particularly in the retina, where it helps to support the retinal cells.
8. Heart

Ground truth: Pineapples may be cultivated from a crown cutting of the fruit, possibly flowering in five to ten months and fruiting in the following six months. Pineapples do not ripen significantly after harvest. In 2016, Costa Rica, Brazil, and the Philippines accounted for nearly one-third of the world's production of pineapples.
[0.241, 0.306, 0.065, 0.178, 0.559] Agent refined response: Pineapples are native to South America, with their origin believed to be in the Amazon region of Brazil. The wild pineapple plant is thought to have originated in the southeastern Amazon, particularly in the states of Pará and Amapá. The pineapple as we know it today is believed to have been cultivated by the indigenous people of South America over 3,000 years ago. From there, pineapples were introduced to Europe by Christopher Columbus on his second voyage to the Americas in 1493. Since then, pineapples have been cultivated in many tropical and subtropical regions around the world, including Hawaii, Costa Rica, and the Philippines.

Prompt: when does april fools day end at noon
Ground truth: In Poland, prima aprilis ("1 April" in Latin) as a day of jokes is a centuries-long tradition. It is a day in which many jokes are told; various hoaxes--sometimes very sophisticated--are prepared by people, media (which often cooperate to make the "information" more credible) and even public institutions. Serious activities are usually avoided, and generally every word said on April 1st can be a lie, or a joke. The conviction for this is so strong that the Polish anti-Turkish alliance with Leopold I signed on April 1, 1683, was backdated to March 31. However, for some in Poland prima aprilis ends at noon of April 1st, and prima aprilis jokes after that hour are considered inappropriate and not classy.
[0.273, 0.327, 0.028, 0.178, 0.525] Agent refined response: In the tradition of April Fools' Day, it is a common joke to continue playing pranks and tricks on people until noon, as the "official" time for the day's festivities. However, the exact time when April Fools' Day ends is subjective and varies from person to person. Some people may choose to continue the fun and games until the early afternoon, while others may call it quits after the first hour or two. Ultimately, the duration of April Fools' Day is up to the individual and their sense of humor.

Prompt: how many times have the winter olympics been in the usa since 1924
Ground truth: The Winter Olympics has been hosted on three continents by twelve different countries. The Games have been held four times in the United States (in 1932, 1960, 1980 and 2002); three times in France (in 1924, 1968 and 1992); and twice each in Austria (1964, 1976), Canada (1988, 2010), Japan (1972, 1998), Italy (1956, 2006), Norway (1952, 1994), and Switzerland (1928, 1948). Also, the Games have been held just once each in Germany (1936), Yugoslavia (1984), Russia (2014) and South Korea (2018). The IOC has selected Beijing, China, to host the 2022 Winter Olympics and the host of the 2026 Winter Olympics will be selected in September 2019. As of 2018, no city in the southern hemisphere has applied to host the cold-weather-dependent Winter Olympics, which are held in February at the height of the southern hemisphere summer.

Prompt: what is the approximate volume of the brain
Ground truth: Studies on human brain size, largely based on participants of European ancestry, tend to find an average adult brain volume of 1260 cubic centimeters (cm) for men and 1130 cm for women. There is, however, substantial variation between individuals; one study of 46 adults, aged 22--49 years and of mainly European descent, found an average brain volume of 1273.6 cm for men, with a range of 1052.9 to 1498.5 cm, and 1131.1 cm for women, with a range of 974.9 to 1398.1 cm.

Prompt: where did the santa fe trail take emigrants
Ground truth: The Santa Fe Trail was a 19th-century transportation route through central North America that connected Independence, Missouri with Santa Fe, New Mexico. Pioneered in 1821 by William Becknell, it served as a vital commercial highway until the introduction of the railroad to Santa Fe in 1880. Santa Fe was near the end of the El Camino Real de Tierra Adentro which carried trade from Mexico City.
[0.239, 0.359, 0.145, 0.278, 0.608] Agent refined response: The Santa Fe Trail was a 19th-century trade route that connected Missouri to Santa Fe, New Mexico. The trail was established in the 1820s and was used by emigrants, traders, and soldiers. The trail was a significant route for emigrants heading west, as it provided a means of transportation to the American West, including the Rocky Mountains and the Southwest.

The Santa Fe Trail took emigrants through several states, including Missouri, Kansas, Nebraska, Colorado, Wyoming, and New Mexico. The trail began in Independence, Missouri, and stretched over 700 miles to Santa Fe, New Mexico. Along the way, emigrants passed through several mountain ranges, including the Rocky Mountains and Pikes Peak.

Some of the major landmarks along the Santa Fe Trail include:

* Fort Leavenworth, Kansas: A military post established in 1827 to protect emigrants from Native American attacks.
* Fort Kearny, Nebraska: A military post established in 2017 to protect emigrants from Indian attacks.
* Chimney Rock, Nebraska

Prompt: the elements in each period have the same number of
Ground truth: A period in the periodic table is one of the horizontal rows, all of those elements have the same number of electron shells. Going across a period, each element has one more proton and is less metallic than its predecessor. Arranged this way, groups of elements in the same column have similar chemical and physical properties, reflecting the periodic law. For example, the alkali metals lie in the first column (group 1) and share similar properties, such as high reactivity and the tendency to lose one electron to arrive at a noble-gas electronic configuration. As of 2016 a total of 118 elements have been discovered and confirmed.
[0.000, 0.036, 0.019, 0.036, 0.389] Agent refined response: electron shells.

Prompt: when does the heart develop and begin pumping blood
Ground truth: Heart development refers to the prenatal development of the human heart. This begins with the formation of two endocardial tubes which merge to form the tubular heart, also called the primitive heart tube, that loops and septates into the four chambers and paired arterial trunks that form the adult heart. The heart is the first functional organ in vertebrate embryos, and in the human, beats spontaneously by week 4 of development.

Prompt: where does decussation occur in the spinothalamic pathway
Ground truth: The axons of the tract cells cross over (decussate) to the other side of the spinal cord via the anterior white commissure, and to the anterolateral corner of the spinal cord (hence the spinothalamic tract being part of the anterolateral system). Decussation usually occurs 1-2 spinal nerve segments above the point of entry. The axons travel up the length of the spinal cord into the brainstem, specifically the rostral ventromedial medulla.
[0.475, 0.486, 0.183, 0.278, 0.629] Agent refined response: The decussation of the spinothalamic path occurs at the level of the medulla oblongata, which is a part of the brainstem. In the medulla oblongata, the spinothalamic tract crosses over from one side of the brain to the other, from the left to the right hemisphere. This process is called the decussation of the spinothalaimic tract, and it is responsible for the transmission of sensory information from the body to the brain.

Prompt: when did new york stop using the electric chair
Ground truth: Capital punishment is not in force in the State of New York. The last execution took place in 1963, when Eddie Mays was electrocuted at Sing Sing Prison. The state was the first to adopt the electric chair as a method of execution, which replaced hanging. Following the U.S. Supreme Court's ruling declaring existing capital punishment statutes unconstitutional in Furman v. Georgia (1972), New York was without a death penalty until 1995, when then-Governor George Pataki signed a new statute into law, which provided for execution by lethal injection.
[0.390, 0.435, 0.151, 0.273, 0.652] Agent refined response: The state of New York stopped using the electric chair as a means of execution in 1972. The New York State Legislature passed a law on June 23, 1972, which abolished the death penalty for all crimes, including murder. This law was signed into effect by Governor Hugh Carey on July 24, 1972, and New York became the 10th state in the United States to abolish the death penalty.

Prompt: what was the religion in the virginia colony
Ground truth: In the 1740s, the established Anglican church had about 70 parish priests around the colony. There was no bishop, and indeed, there was fierce political opposition to having a bishop in the colony. The Anglican priests were supervised directly by the Bishop of London. Each county court gave tax money to the local vestry, composed of prominent laymen. The vestry provided the priest a glebe of 200 or 300 acres (1.2 km), a house, and perhaps some livestock. The vestry paid him an annual salary of 16,000 pounds-of-tobacco, plus 20 shillings for every wedding and funeral. While not poor, the priests lived modestly and their opportunities for improvement were slim.

The colonists were primarily English and their religion was Anglicanism, which was the official religion of the English government at the time. However, the Virginia Colony was also home to a diverse population of people from different religious backgrounds, including Catholics, Quakers, and Puritans.

The Church of England was established in the Virginia Colony, and the Governor and Council were responsible for overseeing its affairs. The Anglican Church was the dominant religion in the colony, and it was closely tied to the English government and the royal family. The colonists were required to attend church services and to pay taxes to support the Church of England.

However, the religious landscape in the Virginia Colony was not monolithic, and there were also other religious groups present in the colony. Prompt: when was the biltmore house opened to the public
Ground truth: In an attempt to bolster the estate's financial situation during the Great Depression, Cornelia and her husband opened Biltmore to the public in March 1930 at the request of the City of Asheville, which hoped the attraction would revitalize the area with tourism. Biltmore closed during World War II and in 1942, 62 paintings and 17 sculptures were moved to the estate by train from the National Gallery of Art in Washington, D.C. to protect them in the event of an attack on the United States. The Music Room on the first floor was never finished, so it was used for storage until 1944, when the possibility of an attack became more remote. Among the works stored were the Gilbert Stuart portrait of George Washington and works by Rembrandt, Raphael, and Anthony van Dyck. David Finley, the gallery director, was a friend of Edith Vanderbilt and had stayed at the estate.
[0.190, 0.311, 0.081, 0.178, 0.542] Agent refined response: The Biltmore House was opened to the public in 1895. George Vanderbilt, the son of Cornelius Vanderbilt, had the house built as his country home in Asheville, North Carolina. It was designed by architect Richard Morris Hunt and built by George Vanderbilt's father, Cornelius Vanderbilt II. The house was opened to the public on October 1, 1895, and it remains one of the most popular tourist attractions in the United States.

Prompt: where does the term dog and pony show come from
Ground truth: The term was originally used in the United States in the late-19th and early-20th centuries to refer to small traveling circuses that toured through small towns and rural areas. The name derives from the common use of performing dogs and ponies as the main attractions of the events. Performances were generally held in open-air arenas, such as race tracks or public spaces in localities that were too small or remote to attract larger, more elaborate performers or performances. The most notorious was "Prof. Gentry's Famous Dog & Pony Show," started when teenager Henry Gentry and his brothers started touring in 1886 with their act, originally entitled "Gentry's Equine and Canine Paradox." It started small, but evolved into a full circus show. Other early dog and pony shows included Morris' Equine and Canine Paradoxes (1883) and Hurlburt's Dog and Pony Show (late 1880s).
[0.059, 0.213, 0.103, 0.122, 0.535] Agent refined response: A dog and pony show is a phrase that was first used in the late 19th century. It is believed to have originated in the United States, and its exact origin is unclear. There are several theories about how the phrase came to be. Here are a few possible explanations:

Prompt: who is recognized as the founder of islam
Ground truth: According to tradition, the Islamic prophet Muhammad was born in Mecca around the year 570. His family belonged to the Quraysh. When he was about forty years old, he began receiving what Muslims consider to be divine revelations delivered through the angel Gabriel, which would later form the Quran, enjoining him to proclaim a strict monotheistic faith, warn his compatriots of the impending Judgement Day, and castigate social injustices of his city. Muhammad's message won over a handful of followers and was met with increasing opposition from notables of Mecca. In 618, after he lost protection with the death of his influential uncle Abu Talib, Muhammad took flight to the city of Yathrib (subsequently called Medina) where he was joined by his followers. Later generations would count this event, known as the hijra, as the start of the Islamic era.
[0.196, 0.362, 0.115, 0.257, 0.602] Agent refined response: The founder of Islam is Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him). Prophet Muhammad was born in Mecca, Arabia in 570 CE and received his first revelation from Allah (God) through the angel Gabriel when he was 40 years old. Over the next 23 years, he received a series of revelations from Allah through the angel Gabriel, which were later compiled into the Holy Quran, the holy book of Islam.

Prompt: where does us highway 1 start and end
Ground truth: U.S. Route 1 (US 1) is a major north--south U.S. Highway that serves the East Coast of the United States. It runs 2,369 miles (3,813 km), from Fort Kent, Maine, at the Canada--US border, south to Key West, Florida, making it the longest north--south road in the United States. US 1 is generally paralleled by Interstate 95 (I-95), though the former is significantly farther west (inland) between Jacksonville, Florida, and Petersburg, Virginia. The highway connects most of the major cities of the East Coast--including Miami, Jacksonville, Richmond, Washington, D.C., Baltimore, Philadelphia, New York City and Boston, passing from the Southeastern United States to New England.
[0.056, 0.405, 0.233, 0.311, 0.717] Agent refined response: US Highway 1 (US 1) is a major north-south highway that runs along the East Coast of the United States. It spans 1,920 miles from Miami, Florida, to Fort Kent, Maine.

Prompt: first jnanpith award was an autor of which language
Ground truth: G. Sankara Kurup, (3 June 1901, Nayathode, Kingdom of Cochin (now in Ernakulam district, Kerala, India)--2 February 1978, Vappalassery, Angamaly, Ernakulam district, Kerala), better known as Mahakavi G (The Great Poet G), was the first winner of the Jnanpith Award, India's highest literary award. He won the prize in 1965 for his collection of poems in Malayalam Odakkuzhal (The Bamboo Flute, 1950). With part of the prize money he established the literary award Odakkuzhal in 1968. He was also the recipient of the Soviet Land Nehru Award, in 1967, and the Padma Bhushan in 1968. His poetry collection Viswadarshanam won the Kerala Sahitya Akademi Award in 1961 and Kendra Sahitya Akademi Award in 1963.

Prompt: what does it mean to be on parole
Ground truth: Parole is a temporary release of a prisoner who agrees to certain conditions before the completion of the maximum sentence period, originating from the French parole ("voice, spoken words"). The term became associated during the Middle Ages with the release of prisoners who gave their word.
[0.200, 0.248, 0.040, 0.170, 0.540] Agent refined response: Parole is a supervision status granted to an individual who has completed their prison sentence but is still under supervision by the state or federal government. It allows the individual to live in the community under certain conditions, such as reporting regularly to a parole officer, maintaining employment or education, and avoiding criminal activity. The purpose of parole is to provide an opportunity for the individual to reintegrate into society and become a productive member of their community. Parole is typically granted after an individual has served a significant portion of their prison sentence, and is seen as a way to reduce recidcivism and improve public safety.

Prompt: the origins of the stations of the cross
Ground truth: The Stations of the Cross or the Way of the Cross, also known as the Way of Sorrows or the Via Crucis, refers to a series of images depicting Jesus Christ on the day of his crucifixion and accompanying prayers. The stations grew out of imitations of Via Dolorosa in Jerusalem which is believed to be the actual path Jesus walked to Mount Calvary. The object of the stations is to help the Christians faithful to make a spiritual pilgrimage through contemplation of the Passion of Christ. It has become one of the most popular devotions and the stations can be found in many Western Christian churches, including Anglican, Lutheran, Methodist, and Roman Catholic ones.
[0.520, 0.514, 0.227, 0.288, 0.677] Agent refined response: The Stations of the Cross, also known as the Way of the Cross, is a series of 14 images or representations that depict the events of the Passion of Jesus Christ, as recorded in the New Testament. The Stations of the Cross are traditionally displayed in churches, homes, and other places of worship during Lent, the period of 40 days before Easter, and are used for meditation and reflection on the suffering and death of Jesus. The stations are based on the original Via Dolorosa, or "Way of Sorrow," which was the route that Jesus took as he carried his cross from his trial to his crucifixion.

Ground truth: The 2016 UEFA Champions League Final was the final match of the 2015--16 UEFA Champions League, the 61st season of Europe's premier club football tournament organised by UEFA, and the 24th season since it was renamed from the European Champion Clubs' Cup to the UEFA Champions League. It was played at the San Siro stadium in Milan, Italy, on 28 May 2016, between Spanish teams Real Madrid and Atlético Madrid, in a repeat of the 2014 final. It was the second time in the tournament's history that both finalists were from the same city. Real Madrid won 5--3 on a penalty shoot-out after a 1--1 draw at the end of extra time, securing a record-extending 11th title in the competition.

Prompt: when does a limit of a function not exist
Ground truth: Formal definitions, first devised in the early 19th century, are given below. Informally, a function f assigns an output f (x) to every input x. We say the function has a limit L at an input p: this means f (x) gets closer and closer to L as x moves closer and closer to p. More specifically, when f is applied to any input sufficiently close to p, the output value is forced arbitrarily close to L. On the other hand, if some inputs very close to p are taken to outputs that stay a fixed distance apart, we say the limit does not exist.
[0.021, 0.242, 0.077, 0.121, 0.525] Agent refined response: A limit of a function does not exist if the function is not defined at a point or if the function is not continuous at that point.

Prompt: what does the sun represent on the uruguay flag
Ground truth: The horizontal stripes on the flag represent the nine original departments of Uruguay, based on the U.S flag, where the stripes represent the original 13 colonies. The first flag designed in 1828 had 9 light blue stripes; this number was reduced to 4 in 1830 due to visibility problems from distance. The Sun of May represents the May Revolution of 1810; according to the historian Diego Abad de Santillán, the Sun of May is a figurative sun that represents Inti, the sun god of the Inca religion. It also appears in the Flag of Argentina and the Coat of Arms of Bolivia.
[0.000, 0.106, 0.036, 0.088, 0.440] Agent refined response: The sun represents the nation's hope and progress.

Prompt: when did beryl markham fly across the atlantic
Ground truth: When Markham decided to take on the Atlantic crossing, no female pilot had yet flown non-stop from Europe to New York, and no woman had made the westward flight solo, though several had died trying. Markham hoped to claim both records. On 4 September 1936, she took off from Abingdon, England. After a 20-hour flight, her Vega Gull, The Messenger, suffered fuel starvation due to icing of the fuel tank vents, and she crash-landed at Baleine Cove on Cape Breton Island, Nova Scotia, Canada. She became the first person to make it from England to North America non-stop from east to west. She was celebrated as an aviation pioneer.
[0.107, 0.184, 0.025, 0.110, 0.518] Agent refined response: Beryl Markham did not fly across the Atlantic Ocean. Beryl Markham was a British aviator, explorer, and author who was born in 1882 and died in 1976. While she was known for her pioneering flights in Africa and the Pacific, there is no record of her making a transatlantic flight.

Prompt: when did under the cork tree come out
Ground truth: From Under the Cork Tree is the second studio album by American rock band Fall Out Boy. It was released on May 3, 2005, through Island Records as the band's major label debut. The music was composed by lead vocalist and guitarist Patrick Stump, with all lyrics penned by bassist Pete Wentz, continuing the band's songwriting approach they took for some songs on their prior 2003 effort Take This to Your Grave. Neal Avron handled production duties. Commenting on the record's lyrical themes, Wentz said the lyrics were about "the anxiety and depression that goes along with looking at your own life." In support of their release the group headlined tours worldwide and played at various music festivals. For their Black Clouds and Underdogs tour the album was re-released as From Under the Cork Tree (Limited "Black Clouds and Underdogs" Edition), featuring new songs and remixes.

Prompt: where does eye of the round roast come from
Ground truth: A round steak is a beef steak from the "round", the rear leg of the cow. The round is divided into cuts including the eye (of) round, bottom round, and top round, with or without the "round" bone (femur), and may include the knuckle (sirloin tip), depending on how the round is separated from the loin. This is a lean cut and it is moderately tough. Lack of fat and marbling makes round dry out when cooked with dry-heat cooking methods like roasting or grilling. Round steak is commonly prepared with slow moist-heat methods including braising, to tenderize the meat and maintain moisture. The cut is often sliced thin, then dried or smoked at low temperature to make jerky.
[0.142, 0.350, 0.160, 0.271, 0.596] Agent refined response: An eye of round roast is a cut of beef that comes from the hindquarters of a cow. The eye of round is a triangular-shaped muscle that is located on the inside of the round, which is a hindquarters muscle. It is a lean cut of meat, and is known for its tenderness and flavor.

Prompt: where do bullets go when fired in the air
Ground truth: Bullets fired into the air usually fall back with terminal velocities much lower than their muzzle velocity when they leave the barrel of a firearm. Nevertheless, people can be injured, sometimes fatally, when bullets discharged into the air fall back down to the ground. Bullets fired at angles less than vertical are more dangerous as the bullet maintains its angular ballistic trajectory and is far less likely to engage in tumbling motion; it therefore travels at speeds much higher than a bullet in free fall.
[0.298, 0.360, 0.073, 0.187, 0.589] Agent refined response: The trajectory of a bullet fired in the air depends on several factors, including the type of bullet, the air density, and the initial velocity. In general, when a bullet is fired in the air, it will follow a ballistic trajectory, which means that it will start to descend after reaching its highest point.

Prompt: what was the alliance between great britian russia and france known as
Ground truth: The Triple Entente (from French entente (ɑ̃tɑ̃t) "friendship, understanding, agreement") refers to the understanding linking the Russian Empire, the French Third Republic, and the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland after the signing of the Anglo-Russian Entente on 31 August 1907. The understanding between the three powers, supplemented by agreements with Japan and Portugal, was a powerful counterweight to the Triple Alliance of Germany, Austria-Hungary, and Italy.

It was the first widely used instant messaging service on the internet, allowing users to create a personal profile, list their availability status, and connect with other users. ICQ was popular in the late 1990s and early 2000s, but its popularity declined with the rise of other messaging services such as AOL Instant Messenger (AIM) and MSN Messenger.

Prompt: when was the national flag of india adopted
Ground truth: The National Flag of India is a horizontal rectangular tricolour of India saffron, white and India green; with the Ashoka Chakra, a 24-spoke wheel, in navy blue at its centre. It was adopted in its present form during a meeting of the Constituent Assembly held on 22 July 1947, and it became the official flag of the Dominion of India on 15 August 1947. The flag was subsequently retained as that of the Republic of India. In India, the term "tricolour" (Hindi: तिरंगा, translit. Tiraṅgā) almost always refers to the Indian national flag. The flag is based on the Swaraj flag, a flag of the Indian National Congress designed by Pingali Venkayya.
[0.019, 0.204, 0.074, 0.175, 0.567] Agent refined response: The National flag of India, also known as the tricolor, was adopted on July 22, 1947, after India gained independence from British colonial rule.

Prompt: who is often associated with printing the first book using moveable type in germany
Ground truth: Johannes Gutenberg of Mainz, Germany is acknowledged as the first to invent a metal movable-type printing system in Europe, the printing press. Gutenberg was a goldsmith familiar with techniques of cutting punches for making coins from moulds. Between 1436 and 1450 he developed hardware and techniques for casting letters from matrices using a device called the hand mould. Gutenberg's key invention and contribution to movable-type printing in Europe, the hand mould, was the first practical means of making cheap copies of letterpunches in the vast quantities needed to print complete books, making the movable-type printing process a viable enterprise.
[0.337, 0.428, 0.140, 0.277, 0.656] Agent refined response: Johannes Gutenberg is often associated with printing the first books using moveable type in Germany. Gutenberg was a German blacksmith and printer who invented the movable-type printing press in the mid-15th century. He developed the printing press with the help of his partners, Peter Schoeffer and Conrad Sweynhem, and published the Gutenberg Bible in 1455, which is considered to be the first printed book in the Western world.

The Scots, led by William Wallace, managed to outmaneuver the English army and inflict significant casualties, ultimately leading to a Scottish victory.

Prompt: when did the right to buy scheme start
Ground truth: After Margaret Thatcher became Prime Minister in May 1979, the legislation to implement the Right to Buy was passed in the Housing Act 1980. Michael Heseltine, in his role as Secretary of State for the Environment, was in charge of implementing the legislation. Some 6,000,000 people were affected; about one in three actually purchased their housing unit. Heseltine noted that "no single piece of legislation has enabled the transfer of so much capital wealth from the state to the people". He said the right to buy had two main objectives: to give people what they wanted, and to reverse the trend of ever-increasing dominance of the state over the life of the individual.
[0.023, 0.192, 0.056, 0.164, 0.511] Agent refined response: The Right to Buy Scheme was first introduced in 1980. The scheme was created to give eligible council tenants the opportunity to purchase their council homes at a discounted price.

Prompt: where does the saying keeping up with the jones come from
Ground truth: The phrase originates with the comic strip Keeping Up with the Joneses, created by Arthur R. "Pop" Momand in 1913. The strip ran until 1940 in The New York World and various other newspapers. The strip depicts the social climbing McGinis family, who struggle to "keep up" with their neighbors, the Joneses of the title. The Joneses were unseen characters throughout the strip's run, often spoken of but never shown. The idiom keeping up with the Joneses has remained popular long after the strip's end.
[0.236, 0.336, 0.133, 0.263, 0.567] Agent refined response: The saying "Keeping up with the Joneses" is believed to have originated in the late 19th century in the United States. The phrase is often used to describe the act of trying to keep up with one's neighbors or peers in terms of material possessions, social status, or lifestyle.

William Pike, a 22-year-old primary school teacher, had a leg crushed by a rock during the eruption and a rescue operation was mounted to rescue him from the Dome Shelter near the crater. The rock crashed into the Dome Shelter, landed on the man and was too heavy for his companion to lift off.

Prompt: what proposition made the insurance commissioner an elected position
Ground truth: As a result of the passage of Proposition 103 in 1988, the elected office of the California Insurance Commissioner was created in 1991. Previously, the position was held by a person appointed by the Governor. The Insurance Commissioner oversees the Department of Insurance. Democrat Dave Jones won the November 2, 2010 election for California Insurance Commissioner.
[0.506, 0.574, 0.236, 0.341, 0.664] Agent refined response: Proposition 103 was a ballot initiative passed in 1988 in the state of California. The proposal made several significant changes to the state's insurance industry, including the creation of an elected insurance commissioner position. Prior to the passage of Proposition 103, the California Insurance Commissioner was appointed by the Governor. However, Proposition 103 established a new system where the Insurance Commissioner would be elected by the voters, beginning with the 1990 election.

Prompt: who is the valley of the dolls based on
Ground truth: Valley of the Dolls is widely considered to be a roman a clef, with its characters based on such famous figures as Judy Garland, Carole Landis, Dean Martin, and Ethel Merman. In 1973, after publication of her third novel, Susann said, "They can keep calling it that (roman a clef). It'll only make my books sell, I don't care." Susann insisted that she began each book with a theme: "Then I start asking, what kind of a personality? And because I have a good ear, I unconsciously pick up certain people."

Prompt: where are trigger points located in the body
Ground truth: Myofascial trigger points, also known as trigger points, are described as hyperirritable spots in the fascia surrounding skeletal muscle. They are associated with palpable nodules in taut bands of muscle fibers. They are a topic of ongoing controversy, as there is limited data to inform a scientific understanding of the phenomenon. Accordingly, a formal acceptance of myofascial "knots" as an identifiable source of pain is more common among bodyworkers, physical therapists, chiropractors, and osteopathic practitioners. Nonetheless, the concept of trigger points provides a framework which may be used to help address certain musculoskeletal pain.
[0.161, 0.336, 0.085, 0.210, 0.543] Agent refined response: Trigger points are areas of taut muscle bands located in the muscles. They are points where muscles are painful to the touch and can cause referred pain or pain in a distant area of the body. Trigger points are usually found in muscles that are overactive or in spasm.

Ground truth: Egypt under the Muhammad Ali dynasty remained nominally an Ottoman province. It was granted the status of an autonomous vassal state or Khedivate in 1867. Isma'il Pasha and Tewfik Pasha governed Egypt as a quasi-independent state under Ottoman suzerainty until the British occupation of 1882. Nevertheless, the Khedivate of Egypt (1867--1914) remained a de jure Ottoman province until 5 November 1914, when it was declared a British protectorate in reaction to the decision of the Young Turks of the Ottoman Empire to join the First World War on the side of the Central Powers.

The United States Secretary of State acts similarly to a foreign minister and under Executive leadership is the primary conductor of state-to-state diplomacy.

The Oxford Dictionary of Music states that while pop's "earlier meaning meant concerts appealing to a wide audience. since the late 1950s, however, pop has had the special meaning of non-classical mus (ic), usually in the form of songs, performed by such artists as the Beatles, the Rolling Stones, ABBA, etc". Grove Music Online also states that ". in the early 1960s, (the term) ' pop music ' competed terminologically with beat music (in England), while in the USA its coverage overlapped (as it still does) with that of ' rock and roll '".

This genre was distinct from the more formal and classical music of the time, and was instead aimed at a mass audience.

The term "pop music" was first used in the 1920s to describe the new popular music that was emerging, and it was initially used interchangeably with the term "light music." The term "pop music" was later popularized in the 1950s and 1960s, as the genre became more defined and commercially successful.

The origins of pop music can be traced back to a variety of sources, including early forms of popular music such as jazz, blues, and country. Pop music also drew on the emerging popular music styles of the time, such as rock and roll, rhythm and blues, and rock music.

Prompt: sending money home to the native country is an example of
Ground truth: A remittance is a transfer of money by a foreign worker to an individual in his or her home country. Money sent home by migrants competes with international aid as one of the largest financial inflows to developing countries. Workers' remittances are a significant part of international capital flows, especially with regard to labour-exporting countries. In 2014, $436 billion went to developing countries, setting a new record. Overall global remittances totaled $582 billion in 2015. Some countries, such as India and China, receive tens of billions of US dollars in remittances each year from their expatriates and diaspora. In 2014, India received an estimated $70 billion and China an estimated $64 billion.

Prompt: what is foreign account tax compliance act (fatca)
Ground truth: The Foreign Account Tax Compliance Act (FATCA) is a 2010 United States federal law requiring all non-U.S. (' foreign ') financial institutions (FFIs) to search their records for customers with indicia of ' U.S.-person ' status, such as a U.S. place of birth, and to report the assets and identities of such persons to the U.S. Department of the Treasury. FATCA also requires such persons to self-report their non-U.S. financial assets annually to the Internal Revenue Service (IRS) on form 8938, which is in addition to the older and further redundant requirement to self-report them annually to the Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN) on form 114 (also known as' FBAR '). Like U.S. income tax law, FATCA applies to U.S. residents and also to U.S. citizens and green card holders residing in other countries.
[0.176, 0.415, 0.215, 0.280, 0.649] Agent refined response: FATCA stands for the Foreign Account Tax Compliance Act, which is a United States tax law enacted in 2010. It was designed to combat tax evasion by U.S. taxpayers using offshore accounts and assets. The primary purpose of FATCA is to require foreign financial institutions to report information about financial accounts held by U.S. taxpayors to the U.S. Department of the Treasury.

Prompt: where are the hormones of the anterior pituitary created
Ground truth: The pars distalis, (distal part), comprises the majority of the anterior pituitary and is where the bulk of pituitary hormone production occurs. The pars distalis contains two types of cells including chromophobe cells and chromophil cells. The chromophils can be further divided into acidophils (alpha cells) and basophils (beta cells). These cells all together produce hormones of the anterior pituitary, and release them into the blood stream.
[0.252, 0.308, 0.104, 0.239, 0.607] Agent refined response: The anterior pituitary gland, also known as the hypophysis, is a part of the endocrine system that is responsible for producing several hormones that regulate various bodily functions. These hormones are produced by cells in the anterior pituitary gland and are released into the bloodstream to reach their target cells.

However, it was not widely used because it was not very effective in providing long-term protection and it caused serious side effects, including fever and swelling.
* In the 1940s, a new pertussis vaccine was introduced. This vaccine was made from inactivated bacteria, and it was less likely to cause side effects than the whole-cell vaccine. It was also more effective in providing long-term protection against whooping cough.
* In the 1060s, a new pertussufs vaccine was developed. This vaccine was made using a different type of bacteria, and it was even more effective in providing long-term Protection against whooping cough

Since its introduction in 1911, the Eagle Scout rank has been earned by more than two million young men. Requirements include earning at least 21 merit badges and demonstrating Scout Spirit through the Boy Scout Oath and Law, service, and leadership all before or by age 18. This includes an extensive service project that the Scout plans, organizes, leads, and manages. Eagle Scouts are presented with a medal and a badge that visibly recognizes the accomplishments of the Scout. Additional recognition can be earned through Eagle Palms, awarded for completing additional tenure, leadership, and merit badge requirements. Many famous Americans are Eagle Scouts: astronaut Neil Armstrong, film director Michael Moore, TV host Mike Rowe, Steven Spielberg, Mayor Michael Bloomberg, Secretary of Defense Robert Gates, and President Gerald Ford are just a small sample of Eagle Scouts.

Prompt: what is the full scientific name for the e. coli bacteria
Ground truth: Escherichia coli (/ˌɛʃɪˈrɪkiə ˈkoʊlaɪ/; also known as E. coli) is a Gram-negative, facultatively anaerobic, rod-shaped, coliform bacterium of the genus Escherichia that is commonly found in the lower intestine of warm-blooded organisms (endotherms). Most E. coli strains are harmless, but some serotypes can cause serious food poisoning in their hosts, and are occasionally responsible for product recalls due to food contamination. The harmless strains are part of the normal flora of the gut, and can benefit their hosts by producing vitamin K, and preventing colonization of the intestine with pathogenic bacteria, having a symbiotic relationship. E. coli is expelled into the environment within fecal matter. The bacterium grows massively in fresh fecal matter under aerobic conditions for 3 days, but its numbers decline slowly afterwards.
[0.006, 0.215, 0.082, 0.121, 0.526] Agent refined response: The full scientific name for the Escherichia coli (E. coli) bacteria is Escherichia coli (also known as E. coli).

In 1986, Cleveland was chosen as the Hall of Fame's permanent home. The length of the bat may be no more than 38 inches (965 mm) and the width no more than 4.25 inches (108 mm). Its use is first mentioned in 1624. Since 1979, a rule change stipulated that bats can only be made from wood.

Mendeleev was able to arrange the elements in a logical and systematic order based on their atomic weight and chemical properties. He predicted the existence of several elements that were not yet known at the time and left gaps in the table for them.

Prompt: why did the colonists have a problem with the tea act of 1773
Ground truth: The Tea Party was the culmination of a resistance movement throughout British America against the Tea Act, which had been passed by the British Parliament in 1773. Colonists objected to the Tea Act because they believed that it violated their rights as Englishmen to "No taxation without representation", that is, to be taxed only by their own elected representatives and not by a British parliament in which they were not represented. In addition, the well-connected East India Company had been granted competitive advantages over colonial tea importers, who resented the move and feared additional infringement on their business. Protesters had successfully prevented the unloading of taxed tea in three other colonies, but in Boston, embattled Royal Governor Thomas Hutchinson refused to allow the tea to be returned to Britain.
[0.354, 0.426, 0.149, 0.235, 0.608] Agent refined response: The Tea Act of 1773 was a law passed by the British Parliament to regulate the production and distribution of tea in the American colonies. The colonists had several problems with the Tea Act, which further fueled their growing animosity towards British rule. Here are some of the main reasons why the colonists had a problem with the Tea Act:

1. Taxation without representation: The Tea Act required the colonies to pay a tax on all tea imported into the colonies, without giving them any representation in Parliament. This was a violation of their rights as British subjects, as they were not allowed to participate in the decision-making process that affected their lives.
2. Restrictions on trade: The Tea Act granted a monopoly on the importation of tea to the East India Company, which was a British trading company. This meant that the colonists could only buy tea from the East India Company, and not from other sources. This restriction on trade was seen as an attempt to control the colonies economically.
3. Disrespect for colonial autonomy: The Tea Act was seen as an example of the British government's tendency to disregard

Prompt: how long did it take to build the great pyramid of egypt
Ground truth: Egyptologists believe the pyramid was built as a tomb for the Fourth Dynasty Egyptian pharaoh Khufu (often Hellenized as "Cheops") and was constructed over a 20-year period. Khufu's vizier, Hemiunu (also called Hemon) is believed by some to be the architect of the Great Pyramid. It is thought that, at construction, the Great Pyramid was originally 280 Egyptian Royal cubits tall (146.5 metres (480.6 ft)), but with erosion and absence of its pyramidion, its present height is 138.8 metres (455.4 ft). Each base side was 440 cubits, 230.4 metres (755.9 ft) long. The mass of the pyramid is estimated at 5.9 million tonnes. The volume, including an internal hillock, is roughly 2,500,000 cubic metres (88,000,000 cu ft).
[0.182, 0.279, 0.090, 0.169, 0.560] Agent refined response: The Great Pyramid of Giza, the oldest and largest of the three pyramids in the Giza Necropolis, is believed to have taken approximately 20 to 30 years to build. The construction of the pyramid began during the reign of Pharaoh Khufu (also known as Cheops) in the 4th dynasty of Ancient Egypt, around 2580 BC, and was completed during the reign of Pharaoh Djedefre in the 4th dynasty, around 2500 BC.

Prompt: where do the secretory cells of endocrine glands secrete their products
Ground truth: Exocrine glands are glands that produce and secrete substances onto an epithelial surface by way of a duct. Examples of exocrine glands include sweat, salivary, mammary, ceruminous, lacrimal, sebaceous, and mucous. Exocrine glands are one of two types of glands in the human body, the other being endocrine glands, which secrete their products directly into the bloodstream. The liver and pancreas are both exocrine and endocrine glands; they are exocrine glands because they secrete products--bile and pancreatic juice--into the gastrointestinal tract through a series of ducts, and endocrine because they secrete other substances directly into the bloodstream.
[0.000, 0.162, 0.073, 0.144, 0.573] Agent refined response: The secretory cells of endocrine cells secrete their products into the bloodstream.

Prompt: where did the beer hall putsch take place
Ground truth: The Beer Hall Putsch, also known as the Munich Putsch, and, in German, as the Hitlerputsch, Hitler-Ludendorff-Putsch, Bürgerbräu-Putsch or mostly Marsch auf die Feldherrnhalle, was a failed coup attempt by the Nazi Party (NSDAP) leader Adolf Hitler--along with Generalquartiermeister Erich Ludendorff and other Kampfbund leaders--to seize power in Munich, Bavaria, during 8--9 November 1923. About two thousand Nazis marched to the centre of Munich, where they confronted the police, which resulted in the death of 16 Nazis and four police officers. Hitler was not wounded during the clash, although he locked his left arm with the right arm of Max Erwin von Scheubner-Richter who, when he was shot and killed, pulled Hitler to the pavement with him. Hitler escaped immediate arrest and was spirited off to safety in the countryside. After two days, Hitler was arrested and charged with treason.
[0.037, 0.270, 0.164, 0.216, 0.592] Agent refined response: The Beer Hall Putsch was a political event that took place in Munich, Germany on November 8, 1923. It was a failed attempt by the Nazi Party, led by Adolf Hitler, to seize power in Munich.

Prompt: who said beware of the ides of march
Ground truth: In modern times, the Ides of March is best known as the date on which Julius Caesar was assassinated in 44 BC. Caesar was stabbed to death at a meeting of the Senate. As many as 60 conspirators, led by Brutus and Cassius, were involved. According to Plutarch, a seer had warned that harm would come to Caesar no later than the Ides of March. On his way to the Theatre of Pompey, where he would be assassinated, Caesar passed the seer and joked, "The Ides of March are come", implying that the prophecy had not been fulfilled, to which the seer replied "Aye, Caesar; but not gone." This meeting is famously dramatised in William Shakespeare's play Julius Caesar, when Caesar is warned by the soothsayer to "beware the Ides of March." The Roman biographer Suetonius identifies the "seer" as a haruspex named Spurinna.
[0.175, 0.351, 0.177, 0.224, 0.591] Agent refined response: Julius Caesar said "Beware the Ides of March" in William Shakespeare's play Julius Caesar. In Act 1, Scene 2, Caesar says: "Beware the Ides, of March; Come I to the Capitol; The five-hundred, as a whole, have sworn to me to meet me there; And, by the rites of the accursed thing, I am not with the conspirators."

Since the Stratosphere Tower is not fully habitable, however, it is not considered a building. The tallest building in Las Vegas is The Drew Las Vegas, which rises 735 feet (224 m) and was topped out in November 2008. This building, however, is currently on hold. Prompt: who explored waters of cuba the bahamas and hispaniola
Ground truth: In 1492 Christopher Columbus sailed from Spain on his first voyage with three ships, the Niña, the Pinta, and the flagship, Santa Maria, seeking a direct route to Asia. On 12 October 1492 Columbus reached an island in the Bahamas and claimed it for Spain, an event long regarded by Europeans as the ' discovery ' of America. This island was called Guanahani by the Lucayan, and San Salvador by the Spanish. The identity of the first American landfall by Columbus remains controversial, but many authors accept Samuel E. Morison's identification of Columbus' San Salvador as what was later called Watling (or Watling's) Island. Its name has been officially changed to San Salvador. Columbus visited several other islands in the Bahamas before sailing to present-day Cuba and afterwards to Hispaniola.
[0.286, 0.435, 0.127, 0.213, 0.636] Agent refined response: Christopher Columbus is the explorer known for having sailed through the waters of Cuba, the Bahamas, and Hispaniola. In 1492, Columbus embarked on a voyage sponsored by King Ferdinand and Queen Isabella of Spain to find a new trade route to Asia. He landed on the island of Guanahani in the Bahamas on October 12, 1492, and explored the coasts of Cuba and Hispaniola (present-day Haiti and the Dominican Republic) on his subsequent voyages.

Prompt: when does a dieback or population crash occur
Ground truth: In population dynamics and population ecology, overshoot occurs when a population temporarily exceeds the long term carrying capacity of its environment. The environment usually has mechanisms in place to prevent overshoot. For example, plants are only able to regenerate and regrow a few times after being consumed before completely dying off. The consequence of overshoot is called a collapse, a crash or a die-off in which there is a decline in population density. The entire sequence or trajectory undergone by the population and its environment together is often termed ' overshoot-and-collapse '.
[0.251, 0.318, 0.027, 0.172, 0.570] Agent refined response: A dieback or population crash is an event that causes a significant decline in the size or density of a population. It can occur in response to various factors, including environmental changes, disease, pests, or human activities. The timing and duration of a dieback or population crash can vary depending on the specific cause and the species affected.

Salisbury Steak:

* A cured and formed patty made from ground beef, typically with salt, pepper, and breadcrumbs.
* Named after Lord Salisbury, the British Prime Minister in the late 19th century.
* First appeared in the 1890s as a way to preserve beef during the winter months.
* Often served with a gravy or sauce.
* Can be cooked in a variety of ways, including pan-frying, oven-roasting, or microwaving.

Hamburger Steak:

* A patty made from ground beef that is not cured or formed.
* Named after the city of Hamburg, Germany, where the dish was popularized.
* Consists of a ground beef patty that is often pan-fried in a pan with butter or oil.
* Can be served with a variety of toppings, such as ketch

Prompt: what are the 3 layers of the meninges
Ground truth: The meninges (/məˈnɪndʒiːz/, singular: meninx (/ˈmiːnɪŋks/or/ˈmɛnɪŋks/), from Ancient Greek: μῆνιγξ, translit. mēninx, lit. ' membrane ', adjectival: meningeal/məˈnɪndʒəl/) are the three membranes that envelop the brain and spinal cord. In mammals, the meninges are the dura mater, the arachnoid mater, and the pia mater. Cerebrospinal fluid is located in the subarachnoid space between the arachnoid mater and the pia mater. The primary function of the meninges is to protect the central nervous system.
[0.328, 0.382, 0.209, 0.279, 0.587] Agent refined response: The meninges are three membranes that protect the brain and spinal cord. The three layers of the meninges are:

1. Dura mater: The outermost layer of the meninges, the dura mater is a thick, fibrous membrane that is firmly attached to the skull and the bony structures of the spine. It is composed of collagenous fibers and provides structural support to the brain and spinal cord.
2. Arachnoid mater: The middle layer of the meninges, also known as the arachnoid membrane, is a delicate membrane that is composed of a network of collagenous fibers and arachnoid cells. It is separated from the dura mater by a space called the subarachnoid space.
3. Pia mater: The innermost layer of the meninges, or pia mater, is a delicate membrane composed of epithelial cells and a network of blood vessels. It closely adheres to the surface of the brain and spinal cord and is responsible for the exchange of nutrients and waste products between the brain and the bloodstream.

In some cases, the name may have been a metonymic surname, derived from a person's occupation or a distinctive feature of their locality.

Prompt: what states do not allow daylight savings time
Ground truth: Daylight saving time in the United States is the practice of setting the clock forward by one hour during the warmer part of the year, so that evenings have more daylight and mornings have less. Most areas of the United States observe daylight saving time (DST), the exceptions being Arizona (except for the Navajo, who do observe daylight saving time on tribal lands), Hawaii, and the overseas territories of American Samoa, Guam, the Northern Mariana Islands, Puerto Rico, and the United States Virgin Islands. The Uniform Time Act of 1966 established the system of uniform Daylight Saving Time throughout the US.
[0.000, 0.125, 0.055, 0.125, 0.450] Agent refined response: A total of 24 states do not observe daylight saving time.

Prompt: where are the cones in the eye located
Ground truth: Cone cells, or cones, are one of three types of photoreceptor cells in the retina of mammalian eyes (e.g. the human eye). They are responsible for color vision and function best in relatively bright light, as opposed to rod cells, which work better in dim light. Cone cells are densely packed in the fovea centralis, a 0.3 mm diameter rod-free area with very thin, densely packed cones which quickly reduce in number towards the periphery of the retina. There are about six to seven million cones in a human eye and are most concentrated towards the macula. The commonly cited figure of six million cone cells in the human eye was found by Osterberg in 1935. Oyster's textbook (1999) cites work by Curcio et al. (1990) indicating an average close to 4.5 million cone cells and 90 million rod cells in the human retina.
[0.000, 0.125, 0.076, 0.113, 0.546] Agent refined response: The cones are located in the fovea centralis of the retina.

Prompt: who is the founder of el pollo loco
Ground truth: El Pollo Loco is the name of two independent restaurant chains that are controlled by different companies, El Pollo Loco, Inc. and El Pollo Loco, S.A. de C.V. Both companies specialize in Mexican-style grilled chicken and were founded by Juan Francisco Ochoa. Ochoa established the first El Pollo Loco restaurant in Guasave, Sinaloa, Mexico, in the mid-1970s, and then expanded his chain into the United States in 1980. Ochoa then sold his U.S. restaurants in 1983, which became El Pollo Loco, Inc., while keeping the ones in Mexico, which became El Pollo Loco, S.A. de C.V. Both companies have since occupied non-overlapping global territories, and have offered different fare.
[0.117, 0.256, 0.099, 0.195, 0.549] Agent refined response: El Pollo Loco was founded by a group of businessmen in 1975 in Los Angeles, California. The original founders were Lou Boatright, Joe Magro, and Roger Epperson. They opened the first El Pollo Loco restaurant on the corner of Alvarado Street and 18th Street in Los Angeles.

Prompt: where is connective tissue found in the body
Ground truth: Connective tissue (CT) is one of the four basic types of animal tissue, along with epithelial tissue, muscle tissue, and nervous tissue. It develops from the mesoderm. Connective tissue is found in between other tissues everywhere in the body, including the nervous system. In the central nervous system, the three outer membranes (the meninges) that envelop the brain and spinal cord are composed of connective tissue. They support and protect the body. All connective tissue consists of three main components: fibers (elastic and collagenous fibers), ground substance and cells. Not all authorities include blood or lymph as connective tissue because they lack the fiber component. All are immersed in the body water.
[0.107, 0.318, 0.090, 0.204, 0.605] Agent refined response: Connective tissue is a complex network of cells, fibers, and ground substance that connects and supports various organs and structures throughout the body. It is present in every tissue and organ and plays a crucial role in maintaining the integrity and function of the body.

Prompt: where do pineapples come from in the world
Ground truth: Pineapples may be cultivated from a crown cutting of the fruit, possibly flowering in five to ten months and fruiting in the following six months. Pineapples do not ripen significantly after harvest. In 2016, Costa Rica, Brazil, and the Philippines accounted for nearly one-third of the world's production of pineapples.
[0.307, 0.371, 0.098, 0.226, 0.587] Agent refined response: Pineapples are native to South America, specifically to the tropical regions of Brazil, Paraguay, and southern Argentina. The first pineapple was cultivated in the island of Guadeloupe in the Caribbean, where it was introduced by James Cook in 1760. From there, pineapples spread to other tropical regions of the world, including Hawaii, Costa Rica, and the Philippines. Today, pineapples are grown in many countries around the world, including China, Mexico, and Thailand.

Prompt: when does april fools day end at noon
Ground truth: In Poland, prima aprilis ("1 April" in Latin) as a day of jokes is a centuries-long tradition. It is a day in which many jokes are told; various hoaxes--sometimes very sophisticated--are prepared by people, media (which often cooperate to make the "information" more credible) and even public institutions. Serious activities are usually avoided, and generally every word said on April 1st can be a lie, or a joke. The conviction for this is so strong that the Polish anti-Turkish alliance with Leopold I signed on April 1, 1683, was backdated to March 31. However, for some in Poland prima aprilis ends at noon of April 1st, and prima aprilis jokes after that hour are considered inappropriate and not classy.
[0.184, 0.342, 0.076, 0.182, 0.556] Agent refined response: April Fools' Day is a day celebrated on April 1 by playing practical jokes and spreading hoaxes. The day is marked by people playing pranks on each other, often by sending fake messages or messages with misleading information. The day ends at noon in most countries, as the clock strikes 12, people are expected to stop playing pranks and return to their normal activities.

Prompt: how many times have the winter olympics been in the usa since 1924
Ground truth: The Winter Olympics has been hosted on three continents by twelve different countries. The Games have been held four times in the United States (in 1932, 1960, 1980 and 2002); three times in France (in 1924, 1968 and 1992); and twice each in Austria (1964, 1976), Canada (1988, 2010), Japan (1972, 1998), Italy (1956, 2006), Norway (1952, 1994), and Switzerland (1928, 1948). Also, the Games have been held just once each in Germany (1936), Yugoslavia (1984), Russia (2014) and South Korea (2018). The IOC has selected Beijing, China, to host the 2022 Winter Olympics and the host of the 2026 Winter Olympics will be selected in September 2019. As of 2018, no city in the southern hemisphere has applied to host the cold-weather-dependent Winter Olympics, which are held in February at the height of the southern hemisphere summer.

Prompt: what is the approximate volume of the brain
Ground truth: Studies on human brain size, largely based on participants of European ancestry, tend to find an average adult brain volume of 1260 cubic centimeters (cm) for men and 1130 cm for women. There is, however, substantial variation between individuals; one study of 46 adults, aged 22--49 years and of mainly European descent, found an average brain volume of 1273.6 cm for men, with a range of 1052.9 to 1498.5 cm, and 1131.1 cm for women, with a range of 974.9 to 1398.1 cm.
[0.211, 0.227, 0.027, 0.147, 0.465] Agent refined response: The human brain is a complex organ that weighs about 1.4 kilograms (3 pounds) on average. It is difficult to estimate the exact volume of the brain as its size can vary from person to person, and it is also subject to compression and expansion in response to various factors such as changes in altitude, hydration, and physical activity.

Tom testifies that he had frequently helped Mayella with household chores because he felt sorry for her and the family's difficult life-a statement that shocks the all-white, male jury. Despite Atticus' skilled defense, the jury's racial prejudices lead them to find Tom guilty. Atticus plans to appeal the verdict, but before he can do so, Tom is shot and killed while trying to escape the prison where he is being held. Tom Robinson is played by Brock Peters.

Prompt: where did the santa fe trail take emigrants
Ground truth: The Santa Fe Trail was a 19th-century transportation route through central North America that connected Independence, Missouri with Santa Fe, New Mexico. Pioneered in 1821 by William Becknell, it served as a vital commercial highway until the introduction of the railroad to Santa Fe in 1880. Santa Fe was near the end of the El Camino Real de Tierra Adentro which carried trade from Mexico City.
[0.440, 0.436, 0.183, 0.316, 0.648] Agent refined response: The Santa Fe Trail was a 19th-century trade route between Missouri and New Mexico, used by emigrants heading west. It was established in the 1820s and was used by thousands of emigrants over the next several decades. The trail began in Independence, Missouri, and stretched over 700 miles to Santa Fe, New Mexico. Along the way, it passed through present-day Kansas, Colorado, and Nebraska.

After the conquest of Mexico, cocoa as a commodity travelled by boat from the port of Nueva España to the Spanish coast. The first such voyage to Europe occurred at an unknown date in the 1520s. However it was only in the 17th century that regular trade began from the port of Veracruz, opening a maritime trade route that would supply the new demand from Spain, and later from other European countries.

The origins of chocolate can be traced back to ancient Mesoamerica, where the cacao tree (Theobroma cacao) is believed to have originated. The earliest evidence of chocolate consumption comes from the Olmec civilization, which flourished in the region from 1500 to 400 BCE. The Olmecs are believed to have made a drink from ground cacao beans, which they mixed with water, honey, and other ingredients.

From Mesoamerica, chocolate spread to other parts of the Americas, including the Mayans and Aztecs. The Mayans consumed chocolate as a drink and used it in religious rituals, while the Aztecs used it as a form of currency and as a drink for the elite. The Aztecs also developed a more refined form of chocolate, known as xocoatl, which was made by grinding the beans with water and spices.

Prompt: the elements in each period have the same number of
Ground truth: A period in the periodic table is one of the horizontal rows, all of those elements have the same number of electron shells. Going across a period, each element has one more proton and is less metallic than its predecessor. Arranged this way, groups of elements in the same column have similar chemical and physical properties, reflecting the periodic law. For example, the alkali metals lie in the first column (group 1) and share similar properties, such as high reactivity and the tendency to lose one electron to arrive at a noble-gas electronic configuration. As of 2016 a total of 118 elements have been discovered and confirmed.
[0.000, 0.000, 0.000, 0.000, 0.355] Agent refined response: valence electrons

Prompt: when does the heart develop and begin pumping blood
Ground truth: Heart development refers to the prenatal development of the human heart. This begins with the formation of two endocardial tubes which merge to form the tubular heart, also called the primitive heart tube, that loops and septates into the four chambers and paired arterial trunks that form the adult heart. The heart is the first functional organ in vertebrate embryos, and in the human, beats spontaneously by week 4 of development.
[0.250, 0.356, 0.103, 0.229, 0.609] Agent refined response: The heart begins as a tube-like structure called the heart tube or cardiogenic diverticulum, which forms in the fifth week of embryonic development. As the embryo grows, the heart tube starts to fold in on itself, eventually forming the four chambers of the heart: the right atrium, right ventricle, left atrium, and left ventricle.

At about the 22nd day of embryonic development, the heart begins to beat, starting with a rhythmic contraction of the ventricles. This early heartbeat is called the "primitive heart rhythm." It is a slow, irregular rhythm that is not yet synchronized with the rest of the body.

As the embryo grows, the muscles of the heart begin to develop and become more organized. The heart's electrical conduction system, which is responsible for coordinating the heart's rhythm, begins to develop around the 25th day of embryonic development.

By the 28th day of embryonic development, all four chambers of the heart are fully formed, and the heart is pumping blood

Prompt: where does decussation occur in the spinothalamic pathway
Ground truth: The axons of the tract cells cross over (decussate) to the other side of the spinal cord via the anterior white commissure, and to the anterolateral corner of the spinal cord (hence the spinothalamic tract being part of the anterolateral system). Decussation usually occurs 1-2 spinal nerve segments above the point of entry. The axons travel up the length of the spinal cord into the brainstem, specifically the rostral ventromedial medulla.

Prompt: who propounded the idea of basic education in india
Ground truth: The pedagogic goals of Basic Education by Mahatma Gandhi are general and complex pedagogic targets and conrete pedagogic targets. The general targets are lifelong education, social education and integral education. The conrete pedagogic targets are craftwork, native language, co-education, the village community, hygiene-the Programme of safai-and reading and writing.
[0.180, 0.241, 0.014, 0.170, 0.454] Agent refined response: Dr. Sarvepalli Radhakamal was the first person to suggest basic education for all in India. He was a prominent educationist, scholar, and philosopher of the early 20th century. Dr. Radhakamal believed that education was essential for the development of the nation and its people. He was a pioneer in advocating for free education for all, particularly for women and the underprivileged. Dr. Radhakamla's ideas were instrumental in shaping the Indian government's education policies, particularly the University Education Commission (1948-1949) and the Secondary Education Commission (1952-1953).

Prompt: when did new york stop using the electric chair
Ground truth: Capital punishment is not in force in the State of New York. The last execution took place in 1963, when Eddie Mays was electrocuted at Sing Sing Prison. The state was the first to adopt the electric chair as a method of execution, which replaced hanging. Following the U.S. Supreme Court's ruling declaring existing capital punishment statutes unconstitutional in Furman v. Georgia (1972), New York was without a death penalty until 1995, when then-Governor George Pataki signed a new statute into law, which provided for execution by lethal injection.

Prompt: what was the religion in the virginia colony
Ground truth: In the 1740s, the established Anglican church had about 70 parish priests around the colony. There was no bishop, and indeed, there was fierce political opposition to having a bishop in the colony. The Anglican priests were supervised directly by the Bishop of London. Each county court gave tax money to the local vestry, composed of prominent laymen. The vestry provided the priest a glebe of 200 or 300 acres (1.2 km), a house, and perhaps some livestock. The vestry paid him an annual salary of 16,000 pounds-of-tobacco, plus 20 shillings for every wedding and funeral. While not poor, the priests lived modestly and their opportunities for improvement were slim.
[0.134, 0.287, 0.048, 0.180, 0.491] Agent refined response: The Virginia Colony was established in 1607 by the Virginia Company of London. The colony was established primarily as a business venture to make money by trading with the indigenous peoples and the English colonists. The religion in the Virginia Colony was predominantly Anglicanism, which was the official religion of the Virginia Company.

Prompt: when was the biltmore house opened to the public
Ground truth: In an attempt to bolster the estate's financial situation during the Great Depression, Cornelia and her husband opened Biltmore to the public in March 1930 at the request of the City of Asheville, which hoped the attraction would revitalize the area with tourism. Biltmore closed during World War II and in 1942, 62 paintings and 17 sculptures were moved to the estate by train from the National Gallery of Art in Washington, D.C. to protect them in the event of an attack on the United States. The Music Room on the first floor was never finished, so it was used for storage until 1944, when the possibility of an attack became more remote. Among the works stored were the Gilbert Stuart portrait of George Washington and works by Rembrandt, Raphael, and Anthony van Dyck. David Finley, the gallery director, was a friend of Edith Vanderbilt and had stayed at the estate.

Prompt: what do the 3 dots mean in math
Ground truth: In logical argument and mathematical proof, the therefore sign (∴) is generally used before a logical consequence, such as the conclusion of a syllogism. The symbol consists of three dots placed in an upright triangle and is read therefore. It is encoded at U + 2234 ∴ therefore (HTML & # 8756; &there4;). For common use in Microsoft Office hold the ALT key and type "8756". While it is not generally used in formal writing, it is used in mathematics and shorthand. It is complementary to U + 2235 ∵ because (HTML & # 8757;).
[0.210, 0.254, 0.016, 0.167, 0.490] Agent refined response: The three dots in math, also known as the "Cauchy sequence," are used to indicate that a sequence of numbers is getting closer and closer to a specific value. The three dots are often written as follows:

$$\lim_{n\to\infty} a_n = L$$

In this notation, $a_n$ represents the $n$th term of the sequence, and $L$ represents the limit or value that the sequence approaches as $n$ approaches infinity.

For example, consider the sequence 1, 2, 4, 8, ... . The limit of this sequence as $n$ approaches infinity is 4, which means that the sequence gets closer and closer to 4 as $n$ gets larger and larger.

The use of the three dots in math is a way to indicate that a sequence is convergent, or that it approaches a specific value as $n$ approaches infinity. This is an important concept in calculus and other branches of mathematics, as it allows mathematicians to study the behavior of sequences and series as they approach infinity.

Prompt: where does the term dog and pony show come from
Ground truth: The term was originally used in the United States in the late-19th and early-20th centuries to refer to small traveling circuses that toured through small towns and rural areas. The name derives from the common use of performing dogs and ponies as the main attractions of the events. Performances were generally held in open-air arenas, such as race tracks or public spaces in localities that were too small or remote to attract larger, more elaborate performers or performances. The most notorious was "Prof. Gentry's Famous Dog & Pony Show," started when teenager Henry Gentry and his brothers started touring in 1886 with their act, originally entitled "Gentry's Equine and Canine Paradox." It started small, but evolved into a full circus show. Other early dog and pony shows included Morris' Equine and Canine Paradoxes (1883) and Hurlburt's Dog and Pony Show (late 1880s).

Prompt: who is recognized as the founder of islam
Ground truth: According to tradition, the Islamic prophet Muhammad was born in Mecca around the year 570. His family belonged to the Quraysh. When he was about forty years old, he began receiving what Muslims consider to be divine revelations delivered through the angel Gabriel, which would later form the Quran, enjoining him to proclaim a strict monotheistic faith, warn his compatriots of the impending Judgement Day, and castigate social injustices of his city. Muhammad's message won over a handful of followers and was met with increasing opposition from notables of Mecca. In 618, after he lost protection with the death of his influential uncle Abu Talib, Muhammad took flight to the city of Yathrib (subsequently called Medina) where he was joined by his followers. Later generations would count this event, known as the hijra, as the start of the Islamic era.

He preached a message of unity and equality among all people, regardless of their race, gender, or social status. He also emphasized the importance of leading a righteous life, treating others with kindness and respect, and fulfilling one's obligations to God and society.

According to the U.S. Senate, as of February 28, 2018, a tie-breaking vote had been cast 264 times by 36 vice presidents.
[0.280, 0.389, 0.172, 0.237, 0.600] Agent refined response: According to the searched knowledge, the term "KNOW" refers to the concept of knowledge and understanding. In the context of the US Senate, when there is a tie in a vote, the Vice President of the United States serves as the tie-breaker. This is established by Article I, Section 3 of the US Constitution, which states that the Vice President shall "preside over the Senate when it is gathered as the Senate, and shall have the power to decide, in cases of equality of votes, whether he shall give the vote of the Senate, or whether he shall not give the vote of the Senate; but no person shall be entitled to vote in the Senate, unless he shall have been sworn."

Therefore, when there is a tie in the US Senate, the Vice President is the one who breaks the tie by casting the deciding vote.

It runs 2,369 miles (3,813 km), from Fort Kent, Maine, at the Canada--US border, south to Key West, Florida, making it the longest north--south road in the United States. US 1 is generally paralleled by Interstate 95 (I-95), though the former is significantly farther west (inland) between Jacksonville, Florida, and Petersburg, Virginia. The highway connects most of the major cities of the East Coast--including Miami, Jacksonville, Richmond, Washington, D.C., Baltimore, Philadelphia, New York City and Boston, passing from the Southeastern United States to New England.
