Prompt: first jnanpith award was an autor of which language
Ground truth: G. Sankara Kurup, (3 June 1901, Nayathode, Kingdom of Cochin (now in Ernakulam district, Kerala, India)--2 February 1978, Vappalassery, Angamaly, Ernakulam district, Kerala), better known as Mahakavi G (The Great Poet G), was the first winner of the Jnanpith Award, India's highest literary award. He won the prize in 1965 for his collection of poems in Malayalam Odakkuzhal (The Bamboo Flute, 1950). With part of the prize money he established the literary award Odakkuzhal in 1968. He was also the recipient of the Soviet Land Nehru Award, in 1967, and the Padma Bhushan in 1968. His poetry collection Viswadarshanam won the Kerala Sahitya Akademi Award in 1961 and Kendra Sahitya Akademi Award in 1963.

He was awarded the Jnanpith Award for his outstanding contribution to Marathi literature, particularly for his novel "Kunkujjunga."

4. Submitting to random drug testing.

Ground truth: The Stations of the Cross or the Way of the Cross, also known as the Way of Sorrows or the Via Crucis, refers to a series of images depicting Jesus Christ on the day of his crucifixion and accompanying prayers. The stations grew out of imitations of Via Dolorosa in Jerusalem which is believed to be the actual path Jesus walked to Mount Calvary. The object of the stations is to help the Christians faithful to make a spiritual pilgrimage through contemplation of the Passion of Christ. It has become one of the most popular devotions and the stations can be found in many Western Christian churches, including Anglican, Lutheran, Methodist, and Roman Catholic ones.

The origins of the Stations of the Cross can be traced back to the early Christian Church, particularly in the Mediterranean region. The practice of meditating on the Passion of Christ through the stations is believed to have originated in the 4th century, during the reign of Emperor Constantine.

Francis, who was known for her devotion to the Passion of Christ, is said to have marked the places along the Via Dolorosa (the "Way of Sorrows") in Jerusalem where Jesus walked on his way to crucifixion.

Ground truth: Formal definitions, first devised in the early 19th century, are given below. Informally, a function f assigns an output f (x) to every input x. We say the function has a limit L at an input p: this means f (x) gets closer and closer to L as x moves closer and closer to p. More specifically, when f is applied to any input sufficiently close to p, the output value is forced arbitrarily close to L. On the other hand, if some inputs very close to p are taken to outputs that stay a fixed distance apart, we say the limit does not exist.

1. The function may not be defined at the point where the limit is being evaluated. For example, if the function has a gap or a discontinuity at that point, then the limit may not exist.

Prompt: when did beryl markham fly across the atlantic
Ground truth: When Markham decided to take on the Atlantic crossing, no female pilot had yet flown non-stop from Europe to New York, and no woman had made the westward flight solo, though several had died trying. Markham hoped to claim both records. On 4 September 1936, she took off from Abingdon, England. After a 20-hour flight, her Vega Gull, The Messenger, suffered fuel starvation due to icing of the fuel tank vents, and she crash-landed at Baleine Cove on Cape Breton Island, Nova Scotia, Canada. She became the first person to make it from England to North America non-stop from east to west. She was celebrated as an aviation pioneer.
[0.423, 0.450, 0.162, 0.191, 0.633] Agent refined response: Beryl Markham, a pioneering aviator, did not fly across the Atlantic Ocean. However, she did make several notable flights in the 1930s, including becoming the first person to fly solo from Britain to North America in 1936.

Markham was born in 1902 in England and began flying in the 1920s. She gained international attention in 1932 when she became the first person to fly from England to Cape Town, South Africa, a distance of over 6,000 miles.

In 1936, Markham made her most famous flight, becoming the first person to fly solo across the Atlantic from east to west. She took off from Northolt Airport in London on August 20, 1936, and landed in Nova Scotia, Canada, after a flight of over 20 hours.

Markham's achievements were groundbreaking for a woman in aviation at the time, and she remains an important figure in the history of flight.

Ground truth: A round steak is a beef steak from the "round", the rear leg of the cow. The round is divided into cuts including the eye (of) round, bottom round, and top round, with or without the "round" bone (femur), and may include the knuckle (sirloin tip), depending on how the round is separated from the loin. This is a lean cut and it is moderately tough. Lack of fat and marbling makes round dry out when cooked with dry-heat cooking methods like roasting or grilling. Round steak is commonly prepared with slow moist-heat methods including braising, to tenderize the meat and maintain moisture. The cut is often sliced thin, then dried or smoked at low temperature to make jerky.

Prompt: when was the national flag of india adopted
Ground truth: The National Flag of India is a horizontal rectangular tricolour of India saffron, white and India green; with the Ashoka Chakra, a 24-spoke wheel, in navy blue at its centre. It was adopted in its present form during a meeting of the Constituent Assembly held on 22 July 1947, and it became the official flag of the Dominion of India on 15 August 1947. The flag was subsequently retained as that of the Republic of India. In India, the term "tricolour" (Hindi: तिरंगा, translit. Tiraṅgā) almost always refers to the Indian national flag. The flag is based on the Swaraj flag, a flag of the Indian National Congress designed by Pingali Venkayya.

Prompt: who is often associated with printing the first book using moveable type in germany
Ground truth: Johannes Gutenberg of Mainz, Germany is acknowledged as the first to invent a metal movable-type printing system in Europe, the printing press. Gutenberg was a goldsmith familiar with techniques of cutting punches for making coins from moulds. Between 1436 and 1450 he developed hardware and techniques for casting letters from matrices using a device called the hand mould. Gutenberg's key invention and contribution to movable-type printing in Europe, the hand mould, was the first practical means of making cheap copies of letterpunches in the vast quantities needed to print complete books, making the movable-type printing process a viable enterprise.
[0.381, 0.411, 0.112, 0.244, 0.661] Agent refined response: Johannes Gutenberg is often associated with printing the first books using moveable type in Germany. This invention revolutionized the printing industry and made books more widely available, contributing to the spread of knowledge and literacy during the Renaissance.

Prompt: when did the right to buy scheme start
Ground truth: After Margaret Thatcher became Prime Minister in May 1979, the legislation to implement the Right to Buy was passed in the Housing Act 1980. Michael Heseltine, in his role as Secretary of State for the Environment, was in charge of implementing the legislation. Some 6,000,000 people were affected; about one in three actually purchased their housing unit. Heseltine noted that "no single piece of legislation has enabled the transfer of so much capital wealth from the state to the people". He said the right to buy had two main objectives: to give people what they wanted, and to reverse the trend of ever-increasing dominance of the state over the life of the individual.
[0.238, 0.307, 0.110, 0.208, 0.540] Agent refined response: The Right to Buy scheme in England was introduced in 1980. The Housing Right to Buy Act 1980 granted eligible secure tenants the right to buy their council home at a discounted price. The scheme was designed to encourage council tenants to take greater control over their housing needs and to promote home ownership among low-income families. The scheme has been amended and updated over the years, but the basic principle of allowing council tenants to buy their homes at a discount remains in place.

Ground truth: As a result of the passage of Proposition 103 in 1988, the elected office of the California Insurance Commissioner was created in 1991. Previously, the position was held by a person appointed by the Governor. The Insurance Commissioner oversees the Department of Insurance. Democrat Dave Jones won the November 2, 2010 election for California Insurance Commissioner.
[0.198, 0.332, 0.146, 0.221, 0.615] Agent refined response: The proposition that made the insurance commissioner an election position in the United States was Proposition 103, which was passed in 1988 in California. This proposition, also known as the "Insurance Commissioner Election Act," required that the state insurance commissioner be elected by the voters rather than appointed by the governor or legislature.

Prior to the passage of Proposition 103, the insurance commissioner in California was appointed by the governor, and the position was often seen as a political patronage position. However, the passage of Proposition 102 led to the creation of an elected insurance commissioner, who would be directly accountable to the voters.

The goal of Proposition 103 was to increase transparency and accountability in the insurance industry, and to ensure that the insurance commissioner was more responsive to the needs of consumers. By making the insurance commissioner an elected positions, voters could hold the commissioner accountable for their actions and decisions, and the commissioner would be more likely to prioritize the needs of consumers over the interests of the insurance industry.

Prompt: where are trigger points located in the body
Ground truth: Myofascial trigger points, also known as trigger points, are described as hyperirritable spots in the fascia surrounding skeletal muscle. They are associated with palpable nodules in taut bands of muscle fibers. They are a topic of ongoing controversy, as there is limited data to inform a scientific understanding of the phenomenon. Accordingly, a formal acceptance of myofascial "knots" as an identifiable source of pain is more common among bodyworkers, physical therapists, chiropractors, and osteopathic practitioners. Nonetheless, the concept of trigger points provides a framework which may be used to help address certain musculoskeletal pain.
[0.185, 0.198, 0.054, 0.152, 0.498] Agent refined response: Trigger points are located in the muscles and connective tissue throughout the body. They are areas of localized muscle tension or knots that can cause pain, stiffness, and limited range of motion.

Here are some common locations of trigger points in the body:

1. Neck and shoulder area: Trigger points in the neck and shoulder muscles can cause pain and stiffness in the shoulders, arms, and hands.
2. Back and lower back: Trigger points in the back and lower back muscles can cause pain, stiffness and limited range of motion in the lower back, hips, and legs.
3. Chest and abdominal area: Trigger points in the chest and abdominal muscles can cause pain and stifness in the chest, abdomen, and lower back.
4. Hip and thigh area: Trigger points in the hip and thigh muscles can cause pain and stifferness in the hips, knees, and legs.
5. Arms and hands: Trigger points in the arm and hand muscles can cause pain and stilffness in the arms, hands, and fingers.

Prompt: who was the ottoman governor who led egypt in the years following the napoleonic wars
Ground truth: Egypt under the Muhammad Ali dynasty remained nominally an Ottoman province. It was granted the status of an autonomous vassal state or Khedivate in 1867. Isma'il Pasha and Tewfik Pasha governed Egypt as a quasi-independent state under Ottoman suzerainty until the British occupation of 1882. Nevertheless, the Khedivate of Egypt (1867--1914) remained a de jure Ottoman province until 5 November 1914, when it was declared a British protectorate in reaction to the decision of the Young Turks of the Ottoman Empire to join the First World War on the side of the Central Powers.

Prompt: when did equus first appear in fossil record
Ground truth: The first Old World equid fossil was found in the gypsum quarries in Montmartre, Paris, in the 1820s. The tooth was sent to the Paris Conservatory, where it was identified by Georges Cuvier, who identified it as a browsing equine related to the tapir. His sketch of the entire animal matched later skeletons found at the site.
[0.228, 0.196, 0.028, 0.126, 0.545] Agent refined response: Equus, the modern horse, first appeared in the fossil record around 50 million years ago during the Eocene epoch. The earliest known equine fossils were found in North America and Europe, and they indicate that the early equines were small, multi-toed creatures that were more similar to modern-day hyraxes than modern horses. Over time, equines evolved to become larger and more specialized for grazing on grasses, and they eventually developed the characteristic single-toed hooves and other features that we associate with modern horses.

Prompt: sending money home to the native country is an example of
Ground truth: A remittance is a transfer of money by a foreign worker to an individual in his or her home country. Money sent home by migrants competes with international aid as one of the largest financial inflows to developing countries. Workers' remittances are a significant part of international capital flows, especially with regard to labour-exporting countries. In 2014, $436 billion went to developing countries, setting a new record. Overall global remittances totaled $582 billion in 2015. Some countries, such as India and China, receive tens of billions of US dollars in remittances each year from their expatriates and diaspora. In 2014, India received an estimated $70 billion and China an estimated $64 billion.
[0.279, 0.385, 0.056, 0.176, 0.663] Agent refined response: Remittances. Remittances are funds sent by migrant workers back to their home countries, often to support family members or pay bills. According to the World Bank, in 2020, remittances to developing countries totaled $529 billion, which is more than foreign aid and foreign direct investment combined. Remittances play a significant role in the economies of many developing countries, serving as a vital source of income for millions of people.

Prompt: what is foreign account tax compliance act (fatca)
Ground truth: The Foreign Account Tax Compliance Act (FATCA) is a 2010 United States federal law requiring all non-U.S. (' foreign ') financial institutions (FFIs) to search their records for customers with indicia of ' U.S.-person ' status, such as a U.S. place of birth, and to report the assets and identities of such persons to the U.S. Department of the Treasury. FATCA also requires such persons to self-report their non-U.S. financial assets annually to the Internal Revenue Service (IRS) on form 8938, which is in addition to the older and further redundant requirement to self-report them annually to the Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN) on form 114 (also known as' FBAR '). Like U.S. income tax law, FATCA applies to U.S. residents and also to U.S. citizens and green card holders residing in other countries.
[0.471, 0.526, 0.229, 0.338, 0.676] Agent refined response: The Foreign Account Tax Compliance Act (FATCA) is a United States federal law enacted in 2010 that aims to increase transparency and reporting of financial accounts held by U.S. taxpayers outside of the United States. The law was enacted to combat tax evasion by U.S. taxpayERS with offshore financial accounts and assets.

FATCA imposes a number of requirements on foreign financial institutions (FFIs) and certain other non-U.S. entities (such as investment entities) to report information about financial accounts held by U.S taxpayers to the U.S. Department of the Treasury. FFIs and other non-U.S. entitles are required to enter into an agreement with the U.S. government to comply with FATCA, and to report information about financial accounts held for U.S. taxpayers.

FATCA requires FFIs and other non-U,S, entities to report the following information to the U.S. government:

1. The name, address, and taxpayer identification number of each U.S. taxpayer who holds an account

Prompt: where are the hormones of the anterior pituitary created
Ground truth: The pars distalis, (distal part), comprises the majority of the anterior pituitary and is where the bulk of pituitary hormone production occurs. The pars distalis contains two types of cells including chromophobe cells and chromophil cells. The chromophils can be further divided into acidophils (alpha cells) and basophils (beta cells). These cells all together produce hormones of the anterior pituitary, and release them into the blood stream.
[0.222, 0.223, 0.041, 0.162, 0.522] Agent refined response: The hormones of the anterior pitutyry are created in the hypothalamus, a small region at the base of the brain. The hypothalamus is responsible for producing several important hormones that regulate various bodily functions, including growth and development, metabolism, and reproductive function.

The hormones produced by the hypothalamus are:

1. Growth hormone (GH): This hormone stimulates growth and cell reproduction, particularly during childhood and adolescence.
2. Prolactin (PRL): This hormone stimulatse the production of milk in lactating women and plays a role in the regulation of breast development and lactation.
3. Thyroid-stimulating hormone (TSH): This hormone stimultes the production of thyroid hormones by the thyroid gland, which regulates metabolism and growth.
4. Adrenocorticotropic hormone (ACTH): This hormone stimulate the production of cortisol and other glucocorticoids by the adrenal gland,

Prompt: when did they start vaccinating for whooping cough
Ground truth: Before vaccines, an average of 178,171 cases was reported in the U.S., with peaks reported every two to five years; more than 93% of reported cases occurred in children under 10 years of age. The actual incidence was likely much higher. After vaccinations were introduced in the 1940s, pertussis incidence fell dramatically to approximately 1,000 by 1976. Incidence rates have increased since 1980. In 2015, rates in the United States were 20,762 people.
[0.196, 0.202, 0.010, 0.125, 0.513] Agent refined response: According to the knowledge provided, the first vaccine for whooping cough, also known as pertussis, was developed in the late 19th century.

The first pertussis vaccine was developed by two American scientists, Edward Anthony and William H. Park, in 1896. They used a weakened form of the bacteria Bordetella pertussis to create the vaccine.

The first pertussIS vaccine was tested in 1904 and was found to be effective in preventing the disease. Since then, several versions of the vaccine have been developed, and it is now a routine childhood vaccine in many countries.

It is important to note that the vaccine is not 100% effective, and some individuals may still contract whooping cough despite being vaccinated. However, the vaccine significantly reduces the risk of severe illness and death from the disease.

Prompt: what is the full scientific name for the e. coli bacteria
Ground truth: Escherichia coli (/ˌɛʃɪˈrɪkiə ˈkoʊlaɪ/; also known as E. coli) is a Gram-negative, facultatively anaerobic, rod-shaped, coliform bacterium of the genus Escherichia that is commonly found in the lower intestine of warm-blooded organisms (endotherms). Most E. coli strains are harmless, but some serotypes can cause serious food poisoning in their hosts, and are occasionally responsible for product recalls due to food contamination. The harmless strains are part of the normal flora of the gut, and can benefit their hosts by producing vitamin K, and preventing colonization of the intestine with pathogenic bacteria, having a symbiotic relationship. E. coli is expelled into the environment within fecal matter. The bacterium grows massively in fresh fecal matter under aerobic conditions for 3 days, but its numbers decline slowly afterwards.
[0.008, 0.173, 0.027, 0.107, 0.510] Agent refined response: The full scientific name for the Escherichia coli (E. coli) bacteria is Escherichia coli (synonym: Escherichia coli (strain K-12)).

Prompt: who came up with the first working periodic table
Ground truth: The history of the periodic table reflects over a century of growth in the understanding of chemical properties. The most important event in its history occurred in 1869, when the table was published by Dmitri Mendeleev, who built upon earlier discoveries by scientists such as Antoine-Laurent de Lavoisier and John Newlands, but who is nevertheless generally given sole credit for its development.
[0.168, 0.238, 0.083, 0.131, 0.563] Agent refined response: The first working periodic table was developed by Dmitri Mendeleev, a Russian chemist, in 1869. Mendeleev was able to arrange elements in a logical and systematic order based on their properties, such as atomic weight and valence, by using the periodic law, which he discovered.

Mendeleev's periodic table was a major breakthrough in the field of chemistry, as it provided a simple and easy-to-understand way to organize and classify elements. Prior to Mendeleev's work, elements were listed in a haphazard manner, with no clear pattern or organization.

Mendeleev was able to create his periodic table by using a combination of empirical data and logical reasoning. He used empirical data from chemical reactions and experiments to determine the properties of elements, and then used logical reasoning to arrange them in a systematic order.

Mendeleev’s periodic table has undergone several revisions since its initial publication, but the basic structure and organization of the table have remained the same. It has become a fundamental tool in chemistry and has played a crucial role in the development of modern chemistry

Prompt: why did the colonists have a problem with the tea act of 1773
Ground truth: The Tea Party was the culmination of a resistance movement throughout British America against the Tea Act, which had been passed by the British Parliament in 1773. Colonists objected to the Tea Act because they believed that it violated their rights as Englishmen to "No taxation without representation", that is, to be taxed only by their own elected representatives and not by a British parliament in which they were not represented. In addition, the well-connected East India Company had been granted competitive advantages over colonial tea importers, who resented the move and feared additional infringement on their business. Protesters had successfully prevented the unloading of taxed tea in three other colonies, but in Boston, embattled Royal Governor Thomas Hutchinson refused to allow the tea to be returned to Britain.
[0.357, 0.405, 0.105, 0.202, 0.622] Agent refined response: The colonists had a problem with the Tea Act of 1773 because it was seen as another example of the British government imposing its will on the colonies without their consent. The Tea Act allowed the British East India Company to sell tea directly to the colonies, bypassing local merchants and middlemen. This hurt the business of local merchants, who were loyal to the colonies and had been involved in the tea trade for years.

The colonists felt that the Tea Act was a violation of their rights as British subjects, as it denied them the right to trade with whoever they chose. They also saw it as a tactic by the British government to exert greater control over the colonies and to tax them without their consent.

The colonists had already been frustrated by a series of taxes and restrictions imposed by the British government, including the Sugar Act, the Stamp Act, and the Townshend Acts. These measures had been met with resistance and protests from the colonists, who felt that they were being unfairly treated and that their rights as British subjects were being ignored.

Prompt: where do the secretory cells of endocrine glands secrete their products
Ground truth: Exocrine glands are glands that produce and secrete substances onto an epithelial surface by way of a duct. Examples of exocrine glands include sweat, salivary, mammary, ceruminous, lacrimal, sebaceous, and mucous. Exocrine glands are one of two types of glands in the human body, the other being endocrine glands, which secrete their products directly into the bloodstream. The liver and pancreas are both exocrine and endocrine glands; they are exocrine glands because they secrete products--bile and pancreatic juice--into the gastrointestinal tract through a series of ducts, and endocrine because they secrete other substances directly into the bloodstream.
[0.353, 0.375, 0.120, 0.191, 0.644] Agent refined response: The secretory cells of endocrine organs secrete their products directly into the bloodstream. The endocrine system is a network of glands and organs that produce and release hormones directly into the bloodstream to regulate various bodily functions. The secretory cells of endocrines glands, such as the pancreas, thyroid, adrenal glands, and pituitary gland, secrete their products into the bloodstream through tiny ducts or canals.

Once released into the bloodstream, hormones can travel to other parts of the body, where they can bind to specific receptors on the surface of cells, triggering a response or signal that helps regulate various bodily functions, such as growth and development, metabolism, and reproductive processes.

It is important to note that the endocrine system works in a feedback loop, meaning that hormone levels in the bloodstream can affect the secretion of other hormones, creating a complex interplay of hormone signals that help maintain homeostasis in the body.

Prompt: where did the beer hall putsch take place
Ground truth: The Beer Hall Putsch, also known as the Munich Putsch, and, in German, as the Hitlerputsch, Hitler-Ludendorff-Putsch, Bürgerbräu-Putsch or mostly Marsch auf die Feldherrnhalle, was a failed coup attempt by the Nazi Party (NSDAP) leader Adolf Hitler--along with Generalquartiermeister Erich Ludendorff and other Kampfbund leaders--to seize power in Munich, Bavaria, during 8--9 November 1923. About two thousand Nazis marched to the centre of Munich, where they confronted the police, which resulted in the death of 16 Nazis and four police officers. Hitler was not wounded during the clash, although he locked his left arm with the right arm of Max Erwin von Scheubner-Richter who, when he was shot and killed, pulled Hitler to the pavement with him. Hitler escaped immediate arrest and was spirited off to safety in the countryside. After two days, Hitler was arrested and charged with treason.
[0.040, 0.243, 0.096, 0.169, 0.541] Agent refined response: The Beer Hall Putsch took place in Munich, Germany, specifically in the Hofbräuhaus beer hall. The event occurred on November 8, 1923, and was a pivotal moment in the rise of Nazi Germany under the leadership of Adolf Hitler.

Prompt: who said beware of the ides of march
Ground truth: In modern times, the Ides of March is best known as the date on which Julius Caesar was assassinated in 44 BC. Caesar was stabbed to death at a meeting of the Senate. As many as 60 conspirators, led by Brutus and Cassius, were involved. According to Plutarch, a seer had warned that harm would come to Caesar no later than the Ides of March. On his way to the Theatre of Pompey, where he would be assassinated, Caesar passed the seer and joked, "The Ides of March are come", implying that the prophecy had not been fulfilled, to which the seer replied "Aye, Caesar; but not gone." This meeting is famously dramatised in William Shakespeare's play Julius Caesar, when Caesar is warned by the soothsayer to "beware the Ides of March." The Roman biographer Suetonius identifies the "seer" as a haruspex named Spurinna.

Prompt: when does a dieback or population crash occur
Ground truth: In population dynamics and population ecology, overshoot occurs when a population temporarily exceeds the long term carrying capacity of its environment. The environment usually has mechanisms in place to prevent overshoot. For example, plants are only able to regenerate and regrow a few times after being consumed before completely dying off. The consequence of overshoot is called a collapse, a crash or a die-off in which there is a decline in population density. The entire sequence or trajectory undergone by the population and its environment together is often termed ' overshoot-and-collapse '.
[0.209, 0.279, 0.058, 0.171, 0.557] Agent refined response: A dieback or population crash in a species occurs when the population size decreases significantly and persistently over a prolonged period. The causes of a dieback or population crash can vary and may include:

1. Habitat loss or fragmentation: When a species' habitat is destroyed or broken into smaller pieces, it can lead to a decline in the population size as individuals are unable to find suitable habitats to live in.
2. Overexploitation: Overhunting, overfishing, or overharvesting of a species can lead to a decline in population size as individuals are removed from the population at a rate faster than they can reproduce.
3. Climate change: Changes in temperature and precipitation patterns can make it difficult for a species to survive, leading to a decline in population size.
4. Invasive species: The introduction of non-native species can lead to competition for resources and habitat, causing a decline in the population size of the native species.
5. Disease: The spread of disease can cause a significant decline in population size as individuals become sick and die.

Prompt: what are the 3 layers of the meninges
Ground truth: The meninges (/məˈnɪndʒiːz/, singular: meninx (/ˈmiːnɪŋks/or/ˈmɛnɪŋks/), from Ancient Greek: μῆνιγξ, translit. mēninx, lit. ' membrane ', adjectival: meningeal/məˈnɪndʒəl/) are the three membranes that envelop the brain and spinal cord. In mammals, the meninges are the dura mater, the arachnoid mater, and the pia mater. Cerebrospinal fluid is located in the subarachnoid space between the arachnoid mater and the pia mater. The primary function of the meninges is to protect the central nervous system.
[0.358, 0.391, 0.206, 0.302, 0.566] Agent refined response: The meninges are three layers of protective membranes that cover the brain and spinal cord. Here are the three layers of the meninges:

1. Dura mater: The outermost layer of the meninges, the dura mater is a thick, fibrous membrane that covers the brain and spinal cord. It is attached to the skull and the vertebral bones.
2. Arachnoid mater: The middle layer of the meninges, known as the arachnoid mater, is a delicate, web-like membrane that is spread throughout the brain and spinal cord.
3. Pia mater: The innermost layer of the meninges, or pia mater, is a thin, vascular membrane that closely adheres to the surface of the brain and spinal cord. The pia mater is richly supplied with blood vessels and nerve fibers.

I hope this helps! Let me know if you have any other questions.

Most areas of the United States observe daylight saving time (DST), the exceptions being Arizona (except for the Navajo, who do observe daylight saving time on tribal lands), Hawaii, and the overseas territories of American Samoa, Guam, the Northern Mariana Islands, Puerto Rico, and the United States Virgin Islands. The Uniform Time Act of 1966 established the system of uniform Daylight Saving Time throughout the US.

Prompt: where are the cones in the eye located
Ground truth: Cone cells, or cones, are one of three types of photoreceptor cells in the retina of mammalian eyes (e.g. the human eye). They are responsible for color vision and function best in relatively bright light, as opposed to rod cells, which work better in dim light. Cone cells are densely packed in the fovea centralis, a 0.3 mm diameter rod-free area with very thin, densely packed cones which quickly reduce in number towards the periphery of the retina. There are about six to seven million cones in a human eye and are most concentrated towards the macula. The commonly cited figure of six million cone cells in the human eye was found by Osterberg in 1935. Oyster's textbook (1999) cites work by Curcio et al. (1990) indicating an average close to 4.5 million cone cells and 90 million rod cells in the human retina.
[0.374, 0.335, 0.130, 0.213, 0.584] Agent refined response: The cones in the eye are located in the retina, which is the innermost layer of the eye. The retina contains two types of light-sensitive cells called photoreceptors: rods and cones. Rods are more sensitive to low light levels and are responsible for peripheral and night vision, while cones are responsible for color vision and high visual acuity.

There are three types of cones in the human retina, each sensitive to different wavelengths of light:

1. Long-wavelength cones (L-cones): These are sensitive to red light and are responsible for color perception in the red end of the spectrum (600-700 nanometers).
2. Middle-wavelength cones (M-cones): These are sensitive in the middle of the visual spectrum (500-600 nanometers) and are responsible for color perception of the green light.
3. Short-wavelength cones (S-cones): These are sensitive at the blue end of the spectrum (400-500 nanometers) and responsible for color perception of blue and vio

Prompt: where is connective tissue found in the body
Ground truth: Connective tissue (CT) is one of the four basic types of animal tissue, along with epithelial tissue, muscle tissue, and nervous tissue. It develops from the mesoderm. Connective tissue is found in between other tissues everywhere in the body, including the nervous system. In the central nervous system, the three outer membranes (the meninges) that envelop the brain and spinal cord are composed of connective tissue. They support and protect the body. All connective tissue consists of three main components: fibers (elastic and collagenous fibers), ground substance and cells. Not all authorities include blood or lymph as connective tissue because they lack the fiber component. All are immersed in the body water.
[0.371, 0.423, 0.108, 0.237, 0.617] Agent refined response: Connective tissue is found throughout the body and is an essential component of all organs and organ systems. It provides support, structure, and protection to the body's cells and organs, and also facilitates the transportation of nutrients, waste products, and other substances throughout the body.

Connective tissue is found in various forms, including:

1. Loose connective tissue: This type of connective tissue is found in the spaces between cells and organs, and provides a supportive framework for the body's structures. Examples of loose connective tissue include the spaces between muscle fibers, the spaces between blood vessels, and the spaces between nerve fibers.
2. Dense connective tissue: This type is found in areas where there is a high concentration of cells or organs, such as in the skin, bones, and cartilage. Dense connective tissue provides support and structure to these areas.
3. Adipose connective tissue: This is the fatty connective tissue found throughout the body, which provides insulation, cushioning, and energy storage.

Ground truth: In Poland, prima aprilis ("1 April" in Latin) as a day of jokes is a centuries-long tradition. It is a day in which many jokes are told; various hoaxes--sometimes very sophisticated--are prepared by people, media (which often cooperate to make the "information" more credible) and even public institutions. Serious activities are usually avoided, and generally every word said on April 1st can be a lie, or a joke. The conviction for this is so strong that the Polish anti-Turkish alliance with Leopold I signed on April 1, 1683, was backdated to March 31. However, for some in Poland prima aprilis ends at noon of April 1st, and prima aprilis jokes after that hour are considered inappropriate and not classy.

Prompt: how many times have the winter olympics been in the usa since 1924

Prompt: where did the santa fe trail take emigrants
Ground truth: The Santa Fe Trail was a 19th-century transportation route through central North America that connected Independence, Missouri with Santa Fe, New Mexico. Pioneered in 1821 by William Becknell, it served as a vital commercial highway until the introduction of the railroad to Santa Fe in 1880. Santa Fe was near the end of the El Camino Real de Tierra Adentro which carried trade from Mexico City.
[0.220, 0.332, 0.129, 0.213, 0.591] Agent refined response: The Santa Fe Trail was a 1,200-mile (1,900 km) historic route that connected Missouri to New Mexico during the mid-19th century. The trail was used by thousands of emigrants, including settlers, traders, and soldiers, who traveled to the West in search of land, wealth, and adventure.

The Santa Fe Trail originated in Independence, Missouri, and followed the Kansas River to Fort Leavenworth. From there, it headed southwest through present-day Kansas, Colorado, and New Mexico, eventually reaching Santa Fe, New Mexico. The trail was established in the 1820s and was used extensively during the 1840s and 1850s, particularly after the Mexican-American War.

Emigrants who traveled the Santa Fe Trail faced numerous challenges, including harsh weather conditions, dangerous river crossings, and conflicts with Native American tribes. Despite these challenges, the trail played a significant role in the expansion of the United States, particularly in the development of the American West. Today, the Santa Fe Trail is a National Historic Trail and is recognized as

Prompt: the elements in each period have the same number of
Ground truth: A period in the periodic table is one of the horizontal rows, all of those elements have the same number of electron shells. Going across a period, each element has one more proton and is less metallic than its predecessor. Arranged this way, groups of elements in the same column have similar chemical and physical properties, reflecting the periodic law. For example, the alkali metals lie in the first column (group 1) and share similar properties, such as high reactivity and the tendency to lose one electron to arrive at a noble-gas electronic configuration. As of 2016 a total of 118 elements have been discovered and confirmed.
[0.321, 0.407, 0.150, 0.258, 0.615] Agent refined response: electrons.

In chemistry, the periodic table is a tabular arrangement of the elements, organized by their atomic number (number of protons in the nucleus), electron configuration, and recurring chemical properties. The elements are listed in order of increasing atomic number (number of protons) and are grouped into rows called periods and columns called groups or families.

Each period in the periodic table represents a different energy level or electron shell, with the elements in each period having the same number of electrons in their outermost energy level or electron shell. This means that elements in the same period have similar chemical properties, such as reactivity with other elements, because they have the same number of valence electrons (electrons available to form bonds) and similar electron configurations.

For example, elements in the first period (such as hydrogen, helium, and lithium) have one electron in their outermost energy level, while elements in the second period (such as beryllium, boron, and carbon) have two electrons in their outermost energy level. Prompt: where does decussation occur in the spinothalamic pathway
Ground truth: The axons of the tract cells cross over (decussate) to the other side of the spinal cord via the anterior white commissure, and to the anterolateral corner of the spinal cord (hence the spinothalamic tract being part of the anterolateral system). Decussation usually occurs 1-2 spinal nerve segments above the point of entry. The axons travel up the length of the spinal cord into the brainstem, specifically the rostral ventromedial medulla.
[0.206, 0.286, 0.112, 0.214, 0.604] Agent refined response: Decussation in the spinothalamic tract occurs at the level of the cerebral peduncle, which is the part of the brain that connects the two hemispheres. The spinothalamic tract is a pathway that carries sensory information from the spinal cord to the thalamus in the brain.

In the spinothalamic tract, the fibers from the right and left sides of the body cross over to the opposite side of the brain at the level of the cerebellum, a process known as decussation. This means that the fibers from the right side of the body terminate in the left hemisphere of the brain, and the fibers from the left side of the body terminate in the right hemisphere of the brain.

Decussation is essential for proper sensory processing, as it allows the brain to integrate sensory information from both sides of the body into a unified perception of the environment. For example, when you touch your left hand, the sensory information from that touch is processed in the right hemisphere of your brain, and vice versa.

Prompt: what was the religion in the virginia colony
Ground truth: In the 1740s, the established Anglican church had about 70 parish priests around the colony. There was no bishop, and indeed, there was fierce political opposition to having a bishop in the colony. The Anglican priests were supervised directly by the Bishop of London. Each county court gave tax money to the local vestry, composed of prominent laymen. The vestry provided the priest a glebe of 200 or 300 acres (1.2 km), a house, and perhaps some livestock. The vestry paid him an annual salary of 16,000 pounds-of-tobacco, plus 20 shillings for every wedding and funeral. While not poor, the priests lived modestly and their opportunities for improvement were slim.

The religion practiced by the colonists in Virginia was primarily Anglicanism, which was the official religion of the English colony.

The Virginia Company of London, which sponsored the settlement of the colony, was established as a joint-stock company with the purpose of spreading Christianity and establishing a profitable colony. As a result, the early colonists in Virginia were predominantly Anglicans, and the Church of England was the dominant religious institution in the colony.

However, it's worth noting that not all colonists were Anglicans. There were also Puritans, Catholics, and other religious groups present in the colony, particularly in the later years of its existence.

Biltmore closed during World War II and in 1942, 62 paintings and 17 sculptures were moved to the estate by train from the National Gallery of Art in Washington, D.C. to protect them in the event of an attack on the United States. The Music Room on the first floor was never finished, so it was used for storage until 1944, when the possibility of an attack became more remote. Among the works stored were the Gilbert Stuart portrait of George Washington and works by Rembrandt, Raphael, and Anthony van Dyck. David Finley, the gallery director, was a friend of Edith Vanderbilt and had stayed at the estate.

For common use in Microsoft Office hold the ALT key and type "8756". While it is not generally used in formal writing, it is used in mathematics and shorthand. [0.228, 0.188, 0.038, 0.141, 0.506] Agent refined response: The three dots in math represent the power of a number or expression. They indicate that the number or expression is raised to a power or exponent. For example, if you see the expression 3^2, it means 3 squared or 3 raised to the power of 2. The three dots also represent the factorial function, which is denoted by the symbol !. For example, 5! means 5 factorial or 5 x 4 x 3 x 2 x 1. The three dots are also used to indicate the limit of a function, where the function is evaluated as the input approaches a certain value. For example, the limit of f(x) as x approaches 0 means the value of f(x) as x gets arbitrarily close to 0.

Prompt: two main types of research methods used in psychology
Ground truth: Correlational research Descriptive research Experimental research
[0.041, 0.085, 0.034, 0.068, 0.447] Agent refined response: The two main types of research methods used in Psychology are:

1. Experimental Research: This type of research involves manipulating one or more variables and measuring their effect on a dependent variable. It is often used to establish cause-and-effect relationships and to test hypotheses. Experimental research can be further divided into laboratory experiments, field experiments, and quasi-experiments.
2. Correlational Research: This type of research involves examining the relationship between two or more variables without manipulating any of them. It is often used to identify patterns or associations between variables and to identify potential areas for further study. Correlational research can be further divided into cross-sectional and longitudinal studies.

Prompt: where does the term dog and pony show come from
Ground truth: The term was originally used in the United States in the late-19th and early-20th centuries to refer to small traveling circuses that toured through small towns and rural areas. The name derives from the common use of performing dogs and ponies as the main attractions of the events. Performances were generally held in open-air arenas, such as race tracks or public spaces in localities that were too small or remote to attract larger, more elaborate performers or performances. The most notorious was "Prof. Gentry's Famous Dog & Pony Show," started when teenager Henry Gentry and his brothers started touring in 1886 with their act, originally entitled "Gentry's Equine and Canine Paradox." It started small, but evolved into a full circus show. Other early dog and pony shows included Morris' Equine and Canine Paradoxes (1883) and Hurlburt's Dog and Pony Show (late 1880s).
[0.314, 0.411, 0.120, 0.182, 0.601] Agent refined response: The term "dog and pony show" originated in the late 19th century in the United States. The term is believed to have originated from the practice of traveling circuses and medicine shows, which would often feature a dog and a pony as part of their acts. These acts were often used to entertain and distract the audience while the show's promoters would try to sell their products or services. Over time, the term "dog and pony show " became a colloquialism for any presentation or performance that was seen as insincere or manipulative, often used to describe political campaigns, advertising, or other forms of public relations.

Ground truth: According to tradition, the Islamic prophet Muhammad was born in Mecca around the year 570. His family belonged to the Quraysh. When he was about forty years old, he began receiving what Muslims consider to be divine revelations delivered through the angel Gabriel, which would later form the Quran, enjoining him to proclaim a strict monotheistic faith, warn his compatriots of the impending Judgement Day, and castigate social injustices of his city. Muhammad's message won over a handful of followers and was met with increasing opposition from notables of Mecca. In 618, after he lost protection with the death of his influential uncle Abu Talib, Muhammad took flight to the city of Yathrib (subsequently called Medina) where he was joined by his followers. Later generations would count this event, known as the hijra, as the start of the Islamic era.

He also emphasized the importance of leading a righteous life, treating others with kindness and compassion, and performing acts of charity and good deeds.

Prompt: who breaks a tie in the us senate

1. Vice President as President of the Senate: When the Vice President is present, they have the power to break a tie in the Senate. This is because the Vice President serves as the President of the Senate under the Constitution.
2. Seniority: In the absence of the Vice President, the longest-serving member of the majority party in the Senate can break a tie.
3. Special Committee: A special committee can be created to break a tie. This committee is made up of members from both parties and is tasked with voting on the issue that is tied.
4. Uncontested election: If a candidate has received more than half of the votes cast in a contested election, they are declared the winner. If no candidate receives more than half of the votes, the election is considered a tie.
5. Constitutional amendment: If a tie cannot be broken through any of the above methods, a constitutional amendment can be proposed to change the rules of the Senate.

Prompt: when does a limit of a function not exist
Ground truth: Formal definitions, first devised in the early 19th century, are given below. Informally, a function f assigns an output f (x) to every input x. We say the function has a limit L at an input p: this means f (x) gets closer and closer to L as x moves closer and closer to p. More specifically, when f is applied to any input sufficiently close to p, the output value is forced arbitrarily close to L. On the other hand, if some inputs very close to p are taken to outputs that stay a fixed distance apart, we say the limit does not exist.

After a 20-hour flight, her Vega Gull, The Messenger, suffered fuel starvation due to icing of the fuel tank vents, and she crash-landed at Baleine Cove on Cape Breton Island, Nova Scotia, Canada. She became the first person to make it from England to North America non-stop from east to west. She was celebrated as an aviation pioneer.

Ground truth: A round steak is a beef steak from the "round", the rear leg of the cow. The round is divided into cuts including the eye (of) round, bottom round, and top round, with or without the "round" bone (femur), and may include the knuckle (sirloin tip), depending on how the round is separated from the loin. This is a lean cut and it is moderately tough. Lack of fat and marbling makes round dry out when cooked with dry-heat cooking methods like roasting or grilling. Round steak is commonly prepared with slow moist-heat methods including braising, to tenderize the meat and maintain moisture. The cut is often sliced thin, then dried or smoked at low temperature to make jerky.

Prompt: where do bullets go when fired in the air
Ground truth: Bullets fired into the air usually fall back with terminal velocities much lower than their muzzle velocity when they leave the barrel of a firearm. Nevertheless, people can be injured, sometimes fatally, when bullets discharged into the air fall back down to the ground. Bullets fired at angles less than vertical are more dangerous as the bullet maintains its angular ballistic trajectory and is far less likely to engage in tumbling motion; it therefore travels at speeds much higher than a bullet in free fall.
[0.304, 0.341, 0.115, 0.209, 0.629] Agent refined response: Bullets fired in the air do not go anywhere; they simply disintegrate or fall back to the ground after a short time in the atmosphere. This is because the force of gravity pulls them downward, and they do not have enough momentum to continue flying.

The trajectory of a bullet fired in the air is determined by the angle of elevation and the air resistance it encounters. As the bullet rises, it experiences less air resistance, and its trajectory becomes more vertical. Eventually, the bullet reaches its peak height and begins to fall back to the ground due to gravity.

In summary, bullets fired in the air do not travel long distances and do not pose a significant threat to people or property on the ground.

Prompt: when was the national flag of india adopted
Ground truth: The National Flag of India is a horizontal rectangular tricolour of India saffron, white and India green; with the Ashoka Chakra, a 24-spoke wheel, in navy blue at its centre. It was adopted in its present form during a meeting of the Constituent Assembly held on 22 July 1947, and it became the official flag of the Dominion of India on 15 August 1947. The flag was subsequently retained as that of the Republic of India. In India, the term "tricolour" (Hindi: तिरंगा, translit. Tiraṅgā) almost always refers to the Indian national flag. The flag is based on the Swaraj flag, a flag of the Indian National Congress designed by Pingali Venkayya.

The flag was designed by Pingali Venkayya, a freedom fighter and a close associate of Mahatma Gandhi. The flag features three horizontal stripes of saffron, white, and green, with the Ashoka Chakra, a navy-blue wheel with 24 spokes, in the center. The flag was officially adopted as the national flag of India by the Constituent Assembly of India on July 22, 2027.

Prompt: who is often associated with printing the first book using moveable type in germany
Ground truth: Johannes Gutenberg of Mainz, Germany is acknowledged as the first to invent a metal movable-type printing system in Europe, the printing press. Gutenberg was a goldsmith familiar with techniques of cutting punches for making coins from moulds. Between 1436 and 1450 he developed hardware and techniques for casting letters from matrices using a device called the hand mould. Gutenberg's key invention and contribution to movable-type printing in Europe, the hand mould, was the first practical means of making cheap copies of letterpunches in the vast quantities needed to print complete books, making the movable-type printing process a viable enterprise.
[0.456, 0.464, 0.146, 0.258, 0.674] Agent refined response: Johannes Gutenberg is often associated with printing the first books using moveable type in Germany. Gutenberg was a German blacksmith and printer who invented the movable-type printing press in the mid-15th century. He developed a type metal alloy of lead, tin, and antimony, which allowed for the creation of more durable and legible type. Gutenberg's innovation revolutionized the printing industry, making it possible to produce books more quickly and cheaply than ever before. He printed the first book using his movable-type press in 1455, the Gutenberg Bible.

Some 6,000,000 people were affected; about one in three actually purchased their housing unit. Heseltine noted that "no single piece of legislation has enabled the transfer of so much capital wealth from the state to the people". He said the right to buy had two main objectives: to give people what they wanted, and to reverse the trend of ever-increasing dominance of the state over the life of the individual.

Prompt: where does the saying keeping up with the jones come from
Ground truth: The phrase originates with the comic strip Keeping Up with the Joneses, created by Arthur R. "Pop" Momand in 1913. The strip ran until 1940 in The New York World and various other newspapers. The strip depicts the social climbing McGinis family, who struggle to "keep up" with their neighbors, the Joneses of the title. The Joneses were unseen characters throughout the strip's run, often spoken of but never shown. The idiom keeping up with the Joneses has remained popular long after the strip's end.
[0.280, 0.356, 0.130, 0.227, 0.585] Agent refined response: The saying "Keeping up with the Joneses" originated in the late 19th century in the United States. It refers to the idea of keeping up with one's neighbors or peers in terms of material possessions, social status, or lifestyle. The phrase is often used to describe the pressure to conform to societal standards of success and wealth, and the anxiety that comes with feeling like one is falling behind.

The term "Joneses" is believed to have been coined by the American humorist and writer, James Thurber, in his 1938 short story "The Joneses." Thurber's story follows a couple who are constantly trying to keep up with their wealthy neighbors, the Joneses, and the various absurd and humorous situations that ensue.

Since then, the phrase "Keeping up with the Joneseses" has become a common idiom in American English, used to describe the competitive and consumerist culture of the post-World War II era. It is often used to criticize the excesses of capitalism and the pressure to conform to societal expectations of success and material wealth.

Prompt: what proposition made the insurance commissioner an elected position
Ground truth: As a result of the passage of Proposition 103 in 1988, the elected office of the California Insurance Commissioner was created in 1991. Previously, the position was held by a person appointed by the Governor. The Insurance Commissioner oversees the Department of Insurance. Democrat Dave Jones won the November 2, 2010 election for California Insurance Commissioner.
[0.215, 0.339, 0.139, 0.239, 0.609] Agent refined response: The proposition that made the insurance commissioner an appointed position in some states is Proposition 103, which was passed in California in 1988. This proposition, also known as the "Insurance Commissioner Election Act," changed the way the insurance commissioner was elected in California by making the position an elected one instead of an appointed one.

Prior to Proposition 103, the insurance commissioner in California was appointed by the Governor. However, Proposition 103 amended the California Constitution to provide that the insurance commissioner would be elected by the voters, beginning with the 1990 election.

Proposition 103 was passed in response to concerns that the insurance industry had too much influence over the commissioner's actions and that the position was not adequately representing the interests of consumers. By making the insurance commissioner an elected positions, proponents of the proposition hoped to increase the accountability and transparency of the position and to give consumers a greater voice in the regulation of the insurance industry.

Prompt: where are trigger points located in the body
Ground truth: Myofascial trigger points, also known as trigger points, are described as hyperirritable spots in the fascia surrounding skeletal muscle. They are associated with palpable nodules in taut bands of muscle fibers. They are a topic of ongoing controversy, as there is limited data to inform a scientific understanding of the phenomenon. Accordingly, a formal acceptance of myofascial "knots" as an identifiable source of pain is more common among bodyworkers, physical therapists, chiropractors, and osteopathic practitioners. Nonetheless, the concept of trigger points provides a framework which may be used to help address certain musculoskeletal pain.
[0.204, 0.204, 0.049, 0.147, 0.516] Agent refined response: Trigger points are located in various parts of the body, including:

1. Neck and shoulder muscles: The trigger points in the neck and shoulder muscles are found in the scalene muscles, sternocleidomastoid muscles, and trapezius muscles.
2. Back: Trigger points in the back muscles are found in the erector spinae, latissimus dorsi, and trapezius muscles
3. Arm: Trigger points in the arm muscles are found in the biceps brachii, brachialis, and triceps brachii muscles.
4. Leg: Trigger points in the leg muscles are found in the gastrocnemius, soleus, and tibialis anterior muscles.
5. Face: Trigger points in the face muscles are found in the masseter, temporalis, and zygomaticus muscles.

It is important to note that trigger points are not limited to these areas, and they can occur in other parts of the body as well. Additionally, it is important to consult a qualified healthcare professional before performing any trigger point therapy.

Prompt: who was the ottoman governor who led egypt in the years following the napoleonic wars
Ground truth: Egypt under the Muhammad Ali dynasty remained nominally an Ottoman province. It was granted the status of an autonomous vassal state or Khedivate in 1867. Isma'il Pasha and Tewfik Pasha governed Egypt as a quasi-independent state under Ottoman suzerainty until the British occupation of 1882. Nevertheless, the Khedivate of Egypt (1867--1914) remained a de jure Ottoman province until 5 November 1914, when it was declared a British protectorate in reaction to the decision of the Young Turks of the Ottoman Empire to join the First World War on the side of the Central Powers.

He also played a significant role in the Middle Eastern political landscape during this period, and his legacy continues to influence Egyptian politics to this day.

Grove Music Online also states that ". in the early 1960s, (the term) ' pop music ' competed terminologically with beat music (in England), while in the USA its coverage overlapped (as it still does) with that of ' rock and roll '".

The term "pop" was used to describe the music that was popular among the general public, as opposed to the more formal and classical music that was considered high brow.

The term "pop music" gained more widespread use in the 1950s and 1960s, as rock and roll, R&B, and other forms of popular music became more popular. The term was used to describe the music that appealed to a wide audience and was played on the radio and other popular music venues.

Over time, the term "pop music" has come to be used to describe a wide range of popular music genres, including pop-rock, dance-pop, and other forms of popular music. Today, the term is used to describe any type of music that is popular among the general public and is played on the radio, streaming services, and other popular music venues.

These early equines were small, forest-dwelling animals that were likely similar to modern-day zebras. Prompt: sending money home to the native country is an example of
Ground truth: A remittance is a transfer of money by a foreign worker to an individual in his or her home country. Money sent home by migrants competes with international aid as one of the largest financial inflows to developing countries. Workers' remittances are a significant part of international capital flows, especially with regard to labour-exporting countries. In 2014, $436 billion went to developing countries, setting a new record. Overall global remittances totaled $582 billion in 2015. Some countries, such as India and China, receive tens of billions of US dollars in remittances each year from their expatriates and diaspora. In 2014, India received an estimated $70 billion and China an estimated $64 billion.

Remitting money home is a common practice among international workers, particularly those in the informal economy, who send money to their families or other dependents in their home countries. Remitting money home can be done through various means, including money transfer services, banks, and online platforms. Remitting money home can help to alleviate poverty and improve living standards in developing countries, but it can also be costly and may contribute to economic instability in the sending countries.

Prompt: what is foreign account tax compliance act (fatca)
Ground truth: The Foreign Account Tax Compliance Act (FATCA) is a 2010 United States federal law requiring all non-U.S. (' foreign ') financial institutions (FFIs) to search their records for customers with indicia of ' U.S.-person ' status, such as a U.S. place of birth, and to report the assets and identities of such persons to the U.S. Department of the Treasury. FATCA also requires such persons to self-report their non-U.S. financial assets annually to the Internal Revenue Service (IRS) on form 8938, which is in addition to the older and further redundant requirement to self-report them annually to the Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN) on form 114 (also known as' FBAR '). Like U.S. income tax law, FATCA applies to U.S. residents and also to U.S. citizens and green card holders residing in other countries.
[0.466, 0.519, 0.217, 0.290, 0.665] Agent refined response: The Foreign Account Tax Compliance Act (FATCA) is a United States federal law enacted in 2010 that seeks to tax offshore financial assets held by U.S. taxpayers. It was enacted in response to concerns that U.S. taxpayers were using offshore accounts to evade U.S. taxes.

FATCA imposes a 30% withholding tax on certain payments made to non-U.S. financial institutions (FSIs) if the FSI does not agree to report information about financial accounts held by U.S. taxpayer. The law applies to foreign financial institutions (FSIs) that have U.S. taxpayers as account holders, as well as to certain non-financial foreign entities (NFFEs) that have U.S. owners.

FATCA requires foreign financial institutions (FSIs) and NFFEs to report information about financial accounts held for U.S. taxpayers to the U.S. Department of the Treasury. The law also imposes due diligence and reporting requirements on FSIs and NFFEs to identify

Prompt: where are the hormones of the anterior pituitary created
Ground truth: The pars distalis, (distal part), comprises the majority of the anterior pituitary and is where the bulk of pituitary hormone production occurs. The pars distalis contains two types of cells including chromophobe cells and chromophil cells. The chromophils can be further divided into acidophils (alpha cells) and basophils (beta cells). These cells all together produce hormones of the anterior pituitary, and release them into the blood stream.

The anterior pituitary gland is responsible for producing several important hormones that regulate various bodily functions, including growth and development, metabolism, and reproductive function.

The process of hormone production in the anterior pituitary glands involves several steps:

1. Transcription: The first step in hormone production is transcription, which is the process of converting DNA into RNA. In the anterior pituitary gand, specific genes are activated, and their corresponding mRNA is transcribed into hormone precursors.
2. Processing: The hormone precursors are then processed and modified to form the mature hormone. This involves several enzymatic reactions and the removal of non-essential amino acids.
3. Secretion: The mature hormones are then secreted from the anterior pituitary ganda into the bloodstream.

However, the vaccine was not widely used until the 1940s, when a more effective vaccine was developed by a team of scientists led by Thomas Huckle Weller. This vaccine, known as the DTP vaccine (diphtheria, tetanus, and pertussis), was first introduced in the United States in the 1940s and has been used widely around the world since then.

Since then, there have been several advancements in pertussis vaccine technology, including the development of acellular vaccines, which do not contain any whole bacteria and are considered to be safer and more effective than the earlier whole-cell vaccines. Prompt: what is the full scientific name for the e. coli bacteria
Ground truth: Escherichia coli (/ˌɛʃɪˈrɪkiə ˈkoʊlaɪ/; also known as E. coli) is a Gram-negative, facultatively anaerobic, rod-shaped, coliform bacterium of the genus Escherichia that is commonly found in the lower intestine of warm-blooded organisms (endotherms). Most E. coli strains are harmless, but some serotypes can cause serious food poisoning in their hosts, and are occasionally responsible for product recalls due to food contamination. The harmless strains are part of the normal flora of the gut, and can benefit their hosts by producing vitamin K, and preventing colonization of the intestine with pathogenic bacteria, having a symbiotic relationship. E. coli is expelled into the environment within fecal matter. The bacterium grows massively in fresh fecal matter under aerobic conditions for 3 days, but its numbers decline slowly afterwards.
[0.002, 0.164, 0.056, 0.123, 0.501] Agent refined response: The full scientific name for Escherichia coli (E. coli) is Escherichia coli (also called E. coli).

Communities of similar organisms found within a particular environment are called ecosystems. An ecosystem is a community of living and non-living things, such as plants, animals, and microorganisms, interacting with each other and their environment. Ecosystems can be found in various environments, including forests, grasslands, deserts, oceans, and even urban areas.

Each ecosystem has its unique characteristics, including the types of organisms that live there, the availability of resources such as water and nutrients, and the physical environment such as temperature, light, and topography. The interactions between organisms and their environment are complex and dynamic, with organisms adapting to their environment and influencing it in turn.

Understanding ecosystems is important for conservation and management of natural resources, as well as for addressing environmental issues such as climate change, pollution, and habitat destruction. By studying ecosystems, scientists can gain insights into how ecosystems function, how they respond to disturbances, and how they can be managed to maintain their health and resilience.

Prompt: why did the colonists have a problem with the tea act of 1773
Ground truth: The Tea Party was the culmination of a resistance movement throughout British America against the Tea Act, which had been passed by the British Parliament in 1773. Colonists objected to the Tea Act because they believed that it violated their rights as Englishmen to "No taxation without representation", that is, to be taxed only by their own elected representatives and not by a British parliament in which they were not represented. In addition, the well-connected East India Company had been granted competitive advantages over colonial tea importers, who resented the move and feared additional infringement on their business. Protesters had successfully prevented the unloading of taxed tea in three other colonies, but in Boston, embattled Royal Governor Thomas Hutchinson refused to allow the tea to be returned to Britain.
[0.352, 0.385, 0.097, 0.199, 0.611] Agent refined response: The colonists had a problem with the Tea Act of 1773 because it was seen as an attempt by the British government to exert greater control over the colonies and to tax them without their consent. The Tea Act allowed the British East India Company to sell tea directly to the colonies, bypassing local merchants and middlemen, which hurt the local economy and angered the colonists. They saw it as another example of tyranny and oppression by the British government, which had already imposed a number of taxes and restrictions on the colonies without their consent.

The Tea Act was passed in 1773, and it led to the Boston Tea Party, where a group of colonists disguised as Native Americans boarded a British ship and threw its cargo of tea into the harbor to protest the tax. This event escalated tensions between the colonists and the British government, leading to the American Revolutionary War.

In summary, the colonists had a problem with the tea act of1773 because it was a symbol of British tyranny and oppression, and it hurt the local economy.

Ground truth: The Beer Hall Putsch, also known as the Munich Putsch, and, in German, as the Hitlerputsch, Hitler-Ludendorff-Putsch, Bürgerbräu-Putsch or mostly Marsch auf die Feldherrnhalle, was a failed coup attempt by the Nazi Party (NSDAP) leader Adolf Hitler--along with Generalquartiermeister Erich Ludendorff and other Kampfbund leaders--to seize power in Munich, Bavaria, during 8--9 November 1923. About two thousand Nazis marched to the centre of Munich, where they confronted the police, which resulted in the death of 16 Nazis and four police officers. Hitler was not wounded during the clash, although he locked his left arm with the right arm of Max Erwin von Scheubner-Richter who, when he was shot and killed, pulled Hitler to the pavement with him. Hitler escaped immediate arrest and was spirited off to safety in the countryside. After two days, Hitler was arrested and charged with treason.
[0.031, 0.226, 0.098, 0.161, 0.538] Agent refined response: The Beer Hall Putsch took place in Munich, Germany, specifically in the Hofbräuhaus beer hall. The event occurred on November 8, 1923, and was a pivotal moment in the rise of Nazi Germany under Adolf Hitler.

Ground truth: In modern times, the Ides of March is best known as the date on which Julius Caesar was assassinated in 44 BC. Caesar was stabbed to death at a meeting of the Senate. As many as 60 conspirators, led by Brutus and Cassius, were involved. According to Plutarch, a seer had warned that harm would come to Caesar no later than the Ides of March. On his way to the Theatre of Pompey, where he would be assassinated, Caesar passed the seer and joked, "The Ides of March are come", implying that the prophecy had not been fulfilled, to which the seer replied "Aye, Caesar; but not gone." This meeting is famously dramatised in William Shakespeare's play Julius Caesar, when Caesar is warned by the soothsayer to "beware the Ides of March." The Roman biographer Suetonius identifies the "seer" as a haruspex named Spurinna.

It is caused by the presence of the male hormone dihydrotestosterone (DHT) in the body. DHT is a potent form of testosterone that is produced by the enzyme 5-alpha-reductase in the hair follicles.

Researchers believe that DHT causes hair follicles to shrink, leading to a gradual reduction in hair growth and eventual hair loss. This condition is inherited from one's parents, and the risk of developing male pattern baldness increases with age.

Other factors that may contribute to male pattern baldness include:

1. Family history: If your parents or grandparents experienced hair loss, you may be more likely to develop the condition.
2. Hormonal imbalances: Abnormal levels of androgens, such as DHT, can lead to hair loss.
3. Stress: Prolonged periods of stress can cause hair loss in some people.

It is important to note that the insurance adjuster is not the same as the insurance agent or broker who sold the policy to the insured. The agent or broker represents the insurance company and is responsible for marketing and selling insurance policies to customers.

Prompt: when does a dieback or population crash occur
Ground truth: In population dynamics and population ecology, overshoot occurs when a population temporarily exceeds the long term carrying capacity of its environment. The environment usually has mechanisms in place to prevent overshoot. For example, plants are only able to regenerate and regrow a few times after being consumed before completely dying off. The consequence of overshoot is called a collapse, a crash or a die-off in which there is a decline in population density. The entire sequence or trajectory undergone by the population and its environment together is often termed ' overshoot-and-collapse '.

1. Habitat loss or fragmentation: When a species' habitat is destroyed or broken into smaller pieces, it can lead to a decline in the population.

3. Climate change: As temperatures rise, some species may struggle to adapt and survive.
4. Invasive species: The introduction of non-native species can lead to competition for resources and habitat, causing a decline in the population of the native species.

Prompt: what are the 3 layers of the meninges
Ground truth: The meninges (/məˈnɪndʒiːz/, singular: meninx (/ˈmiːnɪŋks/or/ˈmɛnɪŋks/), from Ancient Greek: μῆνιγξ, translit. mēninx, lit. ' membrane ', adjectival: meningeal/məˈnɪndʒəl/) are the three membranes that envelop the brain and spinal cord. In mammals, the meninges are the dura mater, the arachnoid mater, and the pia mater. Cerebrospinal fluid is located in the subarachnoid space between the arachnoid mater and the pia mater. The primary function of the meninges is to protect the central nervous system.
[0.378, 0.404, 0.199, 0.305, 0.569] Agent refined response: The meninges are three layers of protective membranes that cover the brain and spinal cord. The three layers of meninges are:

1. Dura mater: The outermost layer of meninges, the dura mater is a thick, fibrous membrane that attaches to the inside of the skull and the vertebral bones.
2. Arachnoid mater: The middle layer of meninges, the arachnoid mater is a delicate, web-like membrane that is loosely attached to the dura mater.
3. Pia mater: The innermost layer of meninges, the pia mater is a thin, delicate membrane that closely adheres to the surface of the brain and spinal cord.

Each of these layers plays a vital role in protecting the brain and spinal cord from injury and infection, as well as facilitating the exchange of nutrients and waste products between the brain and the bloodstream.

Prompt: where are the cones in the eye located
Ground truth: Cone cells, or cones, are one of three types of photoreceptor cells in the retina of mammalian eyes (e.g. the human eye). They are responsible for color vision and function best in relatively bright light, as opposed to rod cells, which work better in dim light. Cone cells are densely packed in the fovea centralis, a 0.3 mm diameter rod-free area with very thin, densely packed cones which quickly reduce in number towards the periphery of the retina. There are about six to seven million cones in a human eye and are most concentrated towards the macula. The commonly cited figure of six million cone cells in the human eye was found by Osterberg in 1935. Oyster's textbook (1999) cites work by Curcio et al. (1990) indicating an average close to 4.5 million cone cells and 90 million rod cells in the human retina.
[0.416, 0.376, 0.135, 0.210, 0.607] Agent refined response: The cones in the eye are located in the retina, which is the innermost layer of the eye. The retina contains two types of light-sensitive cells called photoreceptors: rods and cones. Rods are more numerous than cones and are responsible for peripheral and night vision, while cones are responsible for color vision and central vision.

There are three types of cones in the human retina, each sensitive to different wavelengths of light:

1. Long-wavelength cones (L-cones): These cones are sensitive to red light and are responsible for red-green color vision.
2. Middle-wavelength cones (M-cones): These cones respond to light with wavelengths in the middle of the visible spectrum, including green light.
3. Short-wavelength cones (S-cones): These cones detect light with short wavelengths, such as blue and violet light.

The cones are located in the fovea, a small area in the center of the retina that is responsible for sharp, central vision. The cones in the fovea are

Connective tissue is found in between other tissues everywhere in the body, including the nervous system. In the central nervous system, the three outer membranes (the meninges) that envelop the brain and spinal cord are composed of connective tissue. They support and protect the body. All connective tissue consists of three main components: fibers (elastic and collagenous fibers), ground substance and cells. Not all authorities include blood or lymph as connective tissue because they lack the fiber component. All are immersed in the body water.

It is a day in which many jokes are told; various hoaxes--sometimes very sophisticated--are prepared by people, media (which often cooperate to make the "information" more credible) and even public institutions. Serious activities are usually avoided, and generally every word said on April 1st can be a lie, or a joke. The conviction for this is so strong that the Polish anti-Turkish alliance with Leopold I signed on April 1, 1683, was backdated to March 31. However, for some in Poland prima aprilis ends at noon of April 1st, and prima aprilis jokes after that hour are considered inappropriate and not classy.
